{"title_page": "J. J. Abrams", "text_new": "{{short description|American filmmaker}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = J. J. Abrams\n| image              = J. J. Abrams by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Abrams at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name         = Jeffrey Jacob Abrams\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age |1966|6|27}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| education          = [[Palisades Charter High School]]\n| occupation         = Director, producer, screenwriter, musician, composer, actor, comic book writer\n| years_active       = 1982\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Katie McGrath|1996}}\n| children           = 3\n| parents            = [[Gerald W. Abrams]]<br>[[Carol Ann Abrams|Carol Ann Kelvin]]\n| alma mater         = [[Sarah Lawrence College]]\n}}\n\n'''Jeffrey Jacob Abrams''' (born June 27, 1966)<ref name=britannica>{{cite book|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/J-J-Abrams|title=J.J. Abrams|first=Adam|last=Augustyn|encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]]|accessdate=November 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803015206/https://www.britannica.com/biography/J-J-Abrams|archive-date=August 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> is an American filmmaker. He is known for sabotaging the Star Wars Franchise because he failed with his bad Star Trek Movies, his work in the [[genre]]s of [[Action (genre)|action]], [[Drama (genre)|drama]], and [[science fiction film|science fiction]]. Abrams wrote or produced such films as ''[[Regarding Henry]]''&nbsp;(1991), ''[[Forever Young (1992 film)|Forever Young]]''&nbsp;(1992), ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]''&nbsp;(1998), ''[[Cloverfield]]'' (2008), ''[[Star Trek (film)|Star Trek]]''&nbsp;(2009), and ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]''&nbsp;(2015).\nAbrams has created numerous television  series, including ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'' (co-creator, 1998\u20132002), ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'' (creator, 2001\u20132006), ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'' (co-creator, 2004\u20132010), and ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'' (co-creator, 2008\u20132013). He won two [[Emmy Awards]] for ''Lost'' \u2014 [[Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]].\n\nHis directorial film work includes ''[[Mission: Impossible III]]'' (2006), ''Star Trek'' (2009), ''[[Super 8 (2011 film)|Super 8]]'' (2011), and ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]'' (2013). He also directed, produced and co-wrote ''The Force Awakens'', the seventh episode of the ''[[Star Wars]]'' saga and the first film of the [[Star Wars sequel trilogy|sequel trilogy]]. The film is his highest-grossing, as well as the [[List of highest-grossing films|fourth-highest-grossing film of all time not adjusted for inflation]]. He returned to ''Star Wars'' by directing and co-writing ''[[The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/886927-j-j-abrams-will-direct-star-wars-episode-ix|title=J.J. Abrams to Direct Star Wars: Episode IX! - ComingSoon.net|date=September 12, 2017|access-date=September 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912193946/http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/886927-j-j-abrams-will-direct-star-wars-episode-ix|archive-date=September 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAbrams's frequent collaborators include producer [[Bryan Burk]], producer/director [[Tommy Gormley]], actors [[Greg Grunberg]], [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Keri Russell]], composer [[Michael Giacchino]], writers [[Alex Kurtzman]] and [[Roberto Orci]], cinematographers [[Daniel Mindel]] and [[Larry Fong]], and editors [[Maryann Brandon]] and [[Mary Jo Markey]].\n\n==Early life==\nAbrams was born and raised in New York City,<ref name=britannica /> the son of television producer [[Gerald W. Abrams]] (born 1939) and executive producer [[Carol Ann Abrams]] (n\u00e9e Kelvin; 1942\u20132012).<ref name=variety>{{cite news|title=Carol Ann Abrams dies, Producer, author was mother of J.J. Abrams|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118055047|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 5, 2012|accessdate=June 6, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710074439/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118055047|archive-date=July 10, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> His sister is screenwriter Tracy Rosen.<ref name=variety/>  He attended [[Palisades Charter High School|Palisades High School]]. After graduating from high school, Abrams planned on going to art school rather than a traditional college, but eventually enrolled at [[Sarah Lawrence College]], following his father's advice: \"it's more important that you go off and learn what to make movies about than how to make movies.\"<ref>{{cite AV media | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bN-On2CusDM&t=5m48s&ab_channel=BAFTAGuru | title=J.J. Abrams: On Filmmaking | publisher=[[BAFTA]] Guru | date=May 8, 2013 | access-date=December 28, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105234339/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bN-On2CusDM&t=5m48s&ab_channel=BAFTAGuru | archive-date=January 5, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nAbrams' first job in the movie business was at age 15 when he wrote the music for [[Don Dohler]]'s 1982 horror movie ''[[Nightbeast]]''. During his senior year at college, he teamed with Jill Mazursky to write a feature [[film treatment]].<ref name=college>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/jj-abrams/bio/194178|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wWgWXsXX?url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/jj-abrams/bio/194178|url-status=dead|title=J.J. Abrams|archivedate=February 15, 2011|magazine=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref> Purchased by [[Touchstone Pictures]], the treatment was the basis for ''[[Taking Care of Business (film)|Taking Care of Business]]'', Abrams' first produced film, which starred [[Charles Grodin]] and [[James Belushi]]. He followed with ''[[Regarding Henry]]'', starring [[Harrison Ford]], and ''[[Forever Young (1992 film)|Forever Young]]'', starring [[Mel Gibson]]. He also co-wrote with Mazursky the script for the comedy ''[[Gone Fishin' (film)|Gone Fishin']]'' starring [[Joe Pesci]] and [[Danny Glover]].\n\nIn 1994, he was part of the \"Propellerheads\" with [[Rob Letterman]], Loren Soman, and Andy Waisler, a group of Sarah Lawrence alums experimenting with [[computer animation]] technology. They were contracted by [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]] to develop animation for the film ''[[Shrek]]''.<ref>The Men Who Would Be King: An Almost Epic Tale of Moguls, Movies, and a Company Called DreamWorks pgs. 55\u201356</ref>  Abrams worked on the screenplay for the 1998 film ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'' with producer [[Jerry Bruckheimer]] and director [[Michael Bay]]. That same year, he made his first foray into television with ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'', which ran for four seasons on [[The WB Network]], serving as the series' co-creator (with [[Matt Reeves]]) and executive producer. He also composed its opening [[theme music]].\n\n===2000s===\n[[File:J.J. Abrams by David Shankbone.jpg|right|thumb|Abrams at the 2010 [[Time 100|Time 100 Gala]] in Manhattan]]\nUnder his production company, [[Bad Robot Productions|Bad Robot]], which he founded with [[Bryan Burk]] in 2001,<ref>{{cite web|title=J.J. Abrams not worried about writer's block on 'Fringe' |url=http://shows.ctv.ca/Fringe/article/JJ-Abrams-not-worried-about-writers-block-on-Fringe#c_0 |publisher=[[CTV Television Network|CTV]] |first=Tyrone |last=Warner |date=May 11, 2010 |accessdate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726213716/http://shows.ctv.ca/Fringe/article/JJ-Abrams-not-worried-about-writers-block-on-Fringe |archivedate=July 26, 2010 }}</ref> Abrams created and executive-produced [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Alias (TV series)|Alias]]'' and is co-creator (along with [[Damon Lindelof]] and [[Jeffrey Lieber]]) and was executive producer of ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]].'' As with ''Felicity,'' Abrams also composed the opening [[theme music]] for ''Alias'' and ''Lost''. Abrams directed and wrote the two-part pilot for ''Lost'' and remained active producer for the first half of the season. Also in 2001, Abrams co-wrote and produced the horror-thriller ''[[Joy Ride (2001 film)|Joy Ride]]''.<ref name=Neil>Neil Daniels {{google books|TnsuCgAAQBAJ|Abrams - A Study in Genius: The Unofficial Biography}}</ref> In 2006, he served as executive producer of ''[[What About Brian]]'' and ''[[Six Degrees]]'', also on ABC. He also co-wrote the teleplay for ''Lost''{{'}}s third-season premiere \"[[A Tale of Two Cities (Lost)|A Tale of Two Cities]]\" and the same year, he made his feature directorial debut with ''[[Mission: Impossible&nbsp;III]]'', starring [[Tom Cruise]]. Abrams spoke at the [[TED (conference)|TED]] conference in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=J.J. Abrams's mystery box |url=http://www.ted.com/talks/lang/eng/j_j_abrams_mystery_box.html |publisher=[[TED (conference)|TED]] |date=March 24, 2011 |accessdate=March 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xPZzqZ09?url=http://www.ted.com/talks/lang/eng/j_j_abrams_mystery_box.html |archivedate=March 24, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Abrams produced the [[monster movie]] ''[[Cloverfield]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35377/san-diego-comic-con-2012-dexter-panel-highlights-watch-the-first-two-minutes-of-season-7/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wWgLwzB6?url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35377/jj-abrams-talks-cloverfield-sequel|url-status=dead|title=San Diego Comic-Con 2012: Dexter Panel Highlights; Watch the First Two Minutes of Season 7!|first=Debi|last=Moore|date=July 13, 2012|archivedate=February 15, 2011|website=Dread Central}}</ref> In 2009, he directed the [[science fiction film]] ''[[Star Trek (film)|Star Trek]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/18726/j-j-abrams-on-cloverfield-sequel-were-working-on-something/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wWgL8S4A?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18726|url-status=dead|title=J.J. Abrams on 'Cloverfield' Sequel, \"We're Working on Something\"|first=Brad|last=Miska|date=January 16, 2010|archivedate=February 15, 2011}}</ref> which he produced with ''Lost'' co-creator Damon Lindelof. While it was speculated that they would be writing and producing an adaptation of [[Stephen King]]'s ''[[The Dark Tower (series)|The Dark Tower]]'' series of novels, they publicly stated in November 2009 that they were no longer looking to take on that project.<ref name=\"cf2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/startreknews.php?id=42298 |title=J.J. Abrams on ''Star Trek'' and ''Cloverfield 2'' |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |date=February 23, 2008 |publisher=Comingsoon.net |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225132057/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/startreknews.php?id=42298 |archivedate=February 25, 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2008, Abrams co-created, executive produced, and co-wrote (along with [[Roberto Orci]] and [[Alex Kurtzman]]) the [[Fox Broadcasting Network|FOX]] science fiction series ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'', for which he also composed the theme music. He was featured in the [[2009 MTV Movie Awards]] 1980s-style digital short \"[[Cool Guys Don't Look at Explosions]]\", with [[Andy Samberg]] and [[Will Ferrell]], in which he plays a keyboard solo. [[NBC]] picked up Abrams's ''[[Undercovers (TV series)|Undercovers]]'' as its first new drama series for the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Abrams-Picked-NBC-1018042.aspx |title=NBC Picks Up New J.J. Abrams Drama Series |publisher=TVGuide.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wWgMrDMH?url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Abrams-Picked-NBC-1018042.aspx |archivedate=February 15, 2011 |url-status=live |df= |date=May 3, 2010 }}</ref> However, it was subsequently cancelled by the network in November 2010.\n\nIn 2008, it was reported that Abrams purchased the rights to a ''[[New York Times]]'' article \"Mystery on Fifth Avenue\" about the renovation of an 8.5 million dollar co-op, a division of property originally owned by [[E. F. Hutton & Co.]] and [[Marjorie Merriweather Post]], for six figures and was developing a film titled Mystery on Fifth Avenue, with Paramount Pictures and Bad Robot Productions,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Seigel|first=Tatiana|title=Paramount, Abrams keep house|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117987620?refCatId=13|magazine=Variety|accessdate=June 17, 2008|date=June 17, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424222715/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117987620?refCatId=13|archive-date=April 24, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> and comedy writers Maya Forbes and [[Wally Wolodarsky]] to write the adaptation. According to the article, a wealthy couple Steven B. Klinsky and Maureen Sherry purchased the apartment in 2003 and live there with their four children. Soon after purchasing the apartment, they hired young architectural designer [[Eric Clough]], who devised an elaborately clever \"scavenger hunt\" built into the apartment that involved dozens of historical figures, a fictional book and a soundtrack, woven throughout the apartment in puzzles, riddles, secret panels, compartments, and hidden codes, without the couple's knowledge. The family didn't discover the embedded mystery until months after moving into the apartment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reagan |first=Gillian |title=J.J. Abrams to Produce NYT's Fifth Avenue Mystery |url=http://www.observer.com/2008/j-j-abrams-produce-nyts-fifth-avenue-mystery |newspaper=New York Observer |accessdate=June 18, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080624233139/http://www.observer.com/2008/j-j-abrams-produce-nyts-fifth-avenue-mystery |archivedate=June 24, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Green|first=Penelope|title=Mystery on Fifth Avenue|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/12/garden/12puzzle.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 12, 2008|access-date=February 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223225959/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/12/garden/12puzzle.html|archive-date=February 23, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After Abrams purchased the article, Clough left him an encrypted message in the wall tiles of a [[Christian Louboutin]] shoe store he designed in West Hollywood.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schwartz|first=John|title=Monumentally Mystifying: Power of Secrets Inspires Public Art|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/07/science/07secret.html|newspaper=New York Times|date=December 6, 2010|access-date=February 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170418073715/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/07/science/07secret.html|archive-date=April 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2010s===\n[[File:J.J. Abrams by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Abrams speaking at [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] in 2010]]\nHe wrote and directed the [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] science fiction thriller ''[[Super 8 (2011 film)|Super 8]]'', starring [[Joel Courtney]] and [[Elle Fanning]], while co-producing with [[Steven Spielberg]] and Bryan Burk; it was released on June 10, 2011.<ref name=\"super8confirmed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118018854.html |title=Abrams, Spielberg confirmed for 'Super 8' |accessdate=July 27, 2010 |author=Pamela McClintock |date=May 6, 2010 |work=Variety |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wWgO3c3n?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118018854.html |archivedate=February 15, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> Abrams directed the sequel to ''Star Trek'', ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]'', released in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nextnewmovies.com/j-j-abrams-will-direct-star-trek-2 |title=J.J. Abrams Will Direct STAR TREK 2 |publisher=NextNewMovies |accessdate=December 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402130857/http://www.nextnewmovies.com/j-j-abrams-will-direct-star-trek-2 |archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref> The film ended being considered less original than its predecessor and more of a loose [[remake]] of ''[[Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2018/11/the-wrath-of-khan-director-wasnt-impressed-by-star-trek-into-darkness/|title=The Wrath of Khan director wasn't impressed by Star Trek Into Darkness|date=2018-11-27|website=Flickering Myth|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> Despite critics reacting positively towards the film, [[Nicholas Meyer]] the director of ''Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan'' from which ''Into Darkness'' borrowed lines and plot elements, revealed in 2018, to have been disappointed with the film. Meyer was quoted saying: \"In my sort of artistic worldview, if you\u2019re going to do an homage, you have to add something. You have to put another layer on it, and they didn\u2019t. Just by putting the same words in different characters\u2019 mouths didn't add up to anything, and if you have someone dying in one scene and sort of being resurrected immediately after there's no real drama going on. It just becomes a gimmick or gimmicky, and that's what I found it to be ultimately.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/wrath-khan-director-disappointed-star-trek-into-darkness/|title=Wrath of Khan Director Disappointed by Star Trek Into Darkness|date=November 25, 2018|access-date=December 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055432/https://screenrant.com/wrath-khan-director-disappointed-star-trek-into-darkness/|archive-date=December 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nAbrams announced at the 2013 [[D.I.C.E. Summit]] that [[Bad Robot Productions]] had made a deal with [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] to produce a film based on either the video game title ''[[Portal (video game series)|Portal]]'' or ''[[Half-Life (series)|Half-Life]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graser|first=Marc|title=J.J. Abrams will develop 'Half-Life,' 'Portal' games into films|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118065765|accessdate=February 26, 2013|newspaper=Variety|date=February 6, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130220171307/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118065765/|archive-date=February 20, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 9, 2013, it was announced that Abrams would release a novel, ''[[S. (Dorst novel)|S.]]'', written by [[Doug Dorst]]. The book was released on October 29, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soonyouwillknow.com|title=Stranger|publisher=Soonyouwillknow.com|accessdate=November 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131119154437/http://soonyouwillknow.com/|archive-date=November 19, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 25, 2013, [[The Walt Disney Studios (production company)|The Walt Disney Studios]] and [[Lucasfilm]] officially announced Abrams as director and producer of ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'', the seventh entry in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' film saga, which is a rival saga to ''Star Trek'' for which Abrams previously directed.<ref>{{cite news|title=It's official: Abrams to direct new 'Star Wars' film|url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2013/01/26/its-official-abrams-to-direct-new-star-wars-film/?hpt=hp_c3|accessdate=January 26, 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=January 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127122221/http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2013/01/26/its-official-abrams-to-direct-new-star-wars-film/?hpt=hp_c3|archive-date=January 27, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Disney/Lucasfilm also announced that Bryan Burk and Bad Robot Productions would produce the feature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starwars.com/news/star-wars-is-being-kick-started-with-dynamite-jj-abrams-to-direct-star-wars-episode-vii.html|title=Star Wars Is Being Kick-Started with Dynamite J.J. Abrams to Direct Star Wars: Episode VII|work=StarWars.com|date=January 25, 2013|accessdate=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6eR55nsV3?url=http://www.starwars.com/news/star-wars-is-being-kick-started-with-dynamite|archivedate=January 10, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Following the news that he would direct ''The Force Awakens'', speculation arose as to Abrams's future with Paramount Pictures, with whom he had released all of his previously directed feature work, and which had a first-look deal with his Bad Robot Productions. Paramount vice-chairman Rob Moore stated that Abrams will continue to have a hand in the ''Star Trek'' and ''Mission: Impossible'' franchises going forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2013/01/25/j-j-abrams-directing-star-wars-what-happens-to-star-trek/#/0|title=J.J. Abrams directing 'Star Wars': What happens to 'Star Trek'?|work=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 25, 2013|accessdate=January 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126184555/http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2013/01/25/j-j-abrams-directing-star-wars-what-happens-to-star-trek/#/0|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Abrams directed, produced, and co-wrote the screenplay for, ''The Force Awakens'', working alongside [[Lawrence Kasdan]], following the departure of co-writer [[Michael Arndt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/25/star-wars-jj-abrams-script-episode-vii|title=J.J. Abrams to script as well as direct|date=August 25, 2013|work=Guardian UK|accessdate=October 25, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131028074823/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/oct/25/star-wars-jj-abrams-script-episode-vii|archive-date=October 28, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Star Wars: The Force Awakens'' opened in theaters on December 18, 2015. It grossed over $2 billion at the box office, making him the first director of a $2 billion movie since [[James Cameron]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/star-wars-episode-vii-script-delayed/328150#GeOc2GrVGM0rZHbW.99|title='Star Wars: Episode VII' script delayed|date=December 16, 2013|access-date=December 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216192105/http://www.nme.com/filmandtv/news/star-wars-episode-vii-script-delayed/328150#GeOc2GrVGM0rZHbW.99|archive-date=December 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-chief-reveals-star-wars-693950|title=Disney Chief Reveals 'Star Wars: VII' Casting Almost Complete, Says Film Is Already Shooting (Video)|accessdate=July 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703160617/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-chief-reveals-star-wars-693950|archive-date=July 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite its strong box-office performance and positive reviews from critics, the film was considered by some, including ''Star Wars'' creator [[George Lucas]], to be too similar to the original 1977 film. Lucas felt the film relied too much on \"retro\" nostalgia to his films and too little on creating merits of its own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/film/star-wars-the-force-awakens-10-ways-its-a-remake-of-a-new-hope|title=Star Wars: The Force Awakens - 10 Ways It's A Remake Of A New Hope|last=Hill|first=Sam|date=2015-12-18|website=WhatCulture.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203055901/http://whatculture.com/film/star-wars-the-force-awakens-10-ways-its-a-remake-of-a-new-hope|archive-date=December 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2016/03/mapping-star-wars-force-awakens-characters/|title=The Force Awakens and A New Hope Are More Similar Than You Think|last=McFarland|first=Kevin|date=2016-03-04|work=Wired|access-date=2019-06-19|issn=1059-1028|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204061835/https://www.wired.com/2016/03/mapping-star-wars-force-awakens-characters/|archive-date=December 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Child|first1=Ben|title=Attack of the moans: George Lucas hits out at 'retro' Star Wars: The Force Awakens|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/dec/31/george-lucas-attacks-retro-star-wars-the-force-awakens|accessdate=18 April 2016|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=31 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001032034/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/dec/31/george-lucas-attacks-retro-star-wars-the-force-awakens|archive-date=October 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Peterson|first1=Jeff|title=George Lucas elaborates on his reaction to 'The Force Awakens'|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865645039/George-Lucas-elaborates-on-his-reaction-to-The-Force-Awakens.html?pg=all|accessdate=18 April 2016|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=7 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615220149/https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865645039/George-Lucas-elaborates-on-his-reaction-to-The-Force-Awakens.html?pg=all|archive-date=June 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAbrams served as a producer on the 2016 sci-fi sequel ''[[Star Trek Beyond]]''. And produced ''[[The Cloverfield Paradox]]'', a sequel to ''[[10 Cloverfield Lane]]''. It was released on [[Netflix]] in February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/god-particle-is-cloverfield-3/|title=God Particle is Cloverfield 3|date=October 26, 2016|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030050016/http://www.slashfilm.com/god-particle-is-cloverfield-3|archive-date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"sb\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2018/02/cloverfield-sequel-god-particle-super-bowl-trailer-netflix-streaming-release-1202276386/ | title = Netflix's Ultimate Super Bowl Surprise: 'The Cloverfield Paradox' \u2013 Watch Trailer | first = Anthony | last = D'Alessandro | date = February 4, 2018 | accessdate = February 4, 2018 | website = [[Deadline Hollywood]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180205003638/http://deadline.com/2018/02/cloverfield-sequel-god-particle-super-bowl-trailer-netflix-streaming-release-1202276386/ | archive-date = February 5, 2018 | url-status = live }}</ref> Abrams also returned to produce a [[Mission: Impossible - Fallout#Sequel|sixth ''Mission: Impossible'' film]], alongside [[Tom Cruise]], [[Don Granger]], [[David Ellison]], and Dana Goldberg. The film, titled ''[[Mission: Impossible \u2013 Fallout]]'', was released in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/christopher-mcquarrie-mission-impossible-6-director-writer-1201646710/|title=Christopher McQuarrie Back To Write & Direct 'Mission: Impossible 6'|first=Erik|last=Pedersen|date=November 30, 2015|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030074825/http://deadline.com/2015/11/christopher-mcquarrie-mission-impossible-6-director-writer-1201646710/|archive-date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Also that year, Abrams produced ''[[Overlord (2018 film)|Overlord]]'', a horror film set behind German enemy lines in World War II and directed by [[Julius Avery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/son-of-a-gun-director-bad-robots-nazi-zombie-pic-overlord-1201975823/|title=Bad Robot's D-Day Movie 'Overlord' Finds Director (EXCLUSIVE)|first1=Justin|last1=Kroll|first2=Justin|last2=Kroll|date=February 1, 2017|access-date=December 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131132206/http://variety.com/2017/film/news/son-of-a-gun-director-bad-robots-nazi-zombie-pic-overlord-1201975823/|archive-date=January 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Abrams made his debut as a writer for [[Marvel Comics]], co-authoring the company's title [[Spider-Man]] from September of that year with his son [[Henry Abrams|Henry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marvel.com/articles/comics/j-j-abrams-makes-his-marvel-debut-with-spider-man-1|title=J.J. Abrams Makes His Marvel Debut with 'Spider-Man' #1|first1=Tucker|last1=Marcus|date=June 19, 2019|access-date=September 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624130746/https://www.marvel.com/articles/comics/j-j-abrams-makes-his-marvel-debut-with-spider-man-1|archive-date=June 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The first issue of the comic includes the death of [[Mary-Jane Watson]], and a twelve-year time shift, with the series' protagonist being Ben Parker, son of Peter Parker and Mary Jane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/comics/2019/9/18/20870550/j-j-abrams-spider-man-1-mary-jane-ben-parker-spoilers|title=Spider-Man #1 is a J.J. Abrams comic book in every twist-filled way|first1=Matt|last1=Patches|date=September 18, 2019|access-date=September 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190929012029/https://www.polygon.com/comics/2019/9/18/20870550/j-j-abrams-spider-man-1-mary-jane-ben-parker-spoilers|archive-date=September 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, it was announced by Lucasfilm's president, [[Kathleen Kennedy (producer)|Kathleen Kennedy]], that Abrams would be returning to direct and co-write ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'' with [[Chris Terrio]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Osborn|first1=Alex|title=Star Wars: Episode IX To Be Directed by J.{{nbsp}}J. Abrams|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/09/12/star-wars-episode-ix-to-be-directed-by-jj-abrams|accessdate=September 12, 2017|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=Ziff Davis|date=September 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912151838/http://www.ign.com/articles/2017/09/12/star-wars-episode-ix-to-be-directed-by-jj-abrams|archive-date=September 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The film was released in December 2019; it received mixed reviews from critics and fans,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/star-wars-episode-ix---the-rise-of-skywalker|title=''Star Wars: Episode IX - The Rise of Skywalker'' Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/star_wars_the_rise_of_skywalker/|title=''Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker'' (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> while audience reactions leaned more positively.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/jj-abrams-reacts-last-jedi-rise-of-skywalker |title=J.J. Abrams on ''The Rise of Skywalker'' Critics and Defenders: \"They're All Right\" |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=December 21, 2019 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |first=Anthony |last=Breznican}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/12/20/star-wars-the-rise-of-skywalker-audience-score/ |title=Opening night ''The Rise of Skywalker'' audience score shows a split with critics |publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 20, 2019 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Upcoming projects ===\nIn July 2016, Abrams reported that a [[Star Trek Beyond#Sequel|fourth alternate universe ''Star Trek'' installment]] was in the works and that he is confident that [[Chris Pine]], [[Zachary Quinto]] and [[Chris Hemsworth]] will return for the sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/star-trek-4-chris-hemsworth-jj-abrams/|title=Is Chris Hemsworth Returning for 'Star Trek 4'? J.J. Abrams Teases Next Sequel|date=July 15, 2016|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160717163021/http://collider.com/star-trek-4-chris-hemsworth-jj-abrams/|archive-date=July 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/07/star-trek-4-movie-set-chris-hemsworth-chris-pine-1201787943/|title=Fourth 'Star Trek' Movie A Go At Paramount; Chris Hemsworth Back As Kirk's Father|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|date=July 18, 2016|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719131215/https://deadline.com/2016/07/star-trek-4-movie-set-chris-hemsworth-chris-pine-1201787943/|archive-date=July 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, HBO ordered Abrams' sci-fi drama ''[[Contraband (TV series)|Contraband]]'' to series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/02/01/hbo-orders-j-j-abrams-sci-fi-drama-demimonde-to-series/|title=HBO orders J.J. Abrams sci-fi drama 'Demimonde' to series|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111024804/https://ew.com/tv/2018/02/01/hbo-orders-j-j-abrams-sci-fi-drama-demimonde-to-series/|archive-date=January 11, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Abrams and Avery had reunited to produce and direct, respectively, a superhero thriller film titled ''The Heavy'', with a script written by [[Daniel Casey (screenwriter)|Daniel Casey]]. Paramount and Bad Robot plan to begin filming sometime in 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Kit|first=Borys|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jj-abrams-paramount-plot-superhero-thriller-overlord-director-1108033|title=J.J. Abrams, Paramount Plot Superhero Thriller From ''Overlord'' Director Julius Avery (Exclusive)|date=May 3, 2018|magazine=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=May 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503222707/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jj-abrams-paramount-plot-superhero-thriller-overlord-director-1108033|archive-date=May 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAbrams will produce and [[Guillermo del Toro]] will write and direct a science-fiction action/thriller film titled ''[[Zanbato (film)|Zanbato]]'',<ref>{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|title=Exclusive: Guillermo del Toro to Direct 'Zanbato' for J.J. Abrams' Bad Robot, Paramount|url=https://collider.com/guillermo-del-toro-jj-abrams-zanbato/#bad-robot|date=March 1, 2019|website=Collider|access-date=August 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827031922/http://collider.com/guillermo-del-toro-jj-abrams-zanbato/#bad-robot|archive-date=August 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> which Abrams has been working on since 2011.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nikki|last=Finke|title=Female 'Fringe' Duo Rewriting Top-Secret Screenplay For J.J. Abrams And Paramount|url=https://deadline.com/2011/04/fringe-duo-rewriting-top-secret-script-zanbato-for-j-j-abrams-bad-robot-paramount-123885/|date=April 19, 2011|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=August 27, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827032008/https://deadline.com/2011/04/fringe-duo-rewriting-top-secret-script-zanbato-for-j-j-abrams-bad-robot-paramount-123885/|archive-date=August 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Abrams and his Bad Robot Productions company signed a $250 million five year deal with [[WarnerMedia]], including [[HBO]] and [[Warner Bros. Pictures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/platform/amp/2019/9/12/20862868/warnermedia-jj-abrams-movies-hbo-tv-streaming-bad-robot-productions|title=J.J. Abrams signs exclusivity deal with WarnerMedia reportedly worth $250 million|website=theverge|date=September 12, 2019|access-date=September 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925121623/https://www.theverge.com/platform/amp/2019/9/12/20862868/warnermedia-jj-abrams-movies-hbo-tv-streaming-bad-robot-productions|archive-date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<!-- DO NOT ADD FREQUENT ACTORS OR FREQUENT COLLABORATORS SECTION WITHOUT FURTHER DISCUSSION ON TALK PAGE ~~~~ -->\n\n== Unrealized projects ==\n{{main|J. J. Abrams's unrealized projects}}\n\nIn 1989, Abrams met [[Steven Spielberg]] at a film festival, where Spielberg spoke about a possible [[Who Framed Roger Rabbit 2|''Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' sequel]], with Abrams as a possible writer and with [[Robert Zemeckis]] as producer.<ref name=\"slashfilm.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/who-framed-roger-rabbit-2/|title=J.J. Abrams Once Had a Pitch for Who Framed Roger Rabbit 2|date=March 12, 2016|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030142233/http://www.slashfilm.com/who-framed-roger-rabbit-2/|archive-date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Nothing came up from this project, although Abrams has some storyboards for a ''[[Roger Rabbit]]'' short.<ref name=\"slashfilm.com\"/>\n\nIn July 2002, Abrams wrote a script for a possible fifth [[Superman]] film entitled ''[[Superman: Flyby]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impossiblefunky.com/archives/issue_15/15_superman.asp?IshNum=15|title=Cashiers du Cinemart Issue 15|date=February 16, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216230219/http://www.impossiblefunky.com/archives/issue_15/15_superman.asp?IshNum=15|archivedate=February 16, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Brett Ratner]] and [[McG]] entered into talks to direct,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/17/ratner-talks-superman|title=Ratner Talks Superman|last=Stax|date=September 17, 2002|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421042508/http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/09/17/ratner-talks-superman|archive-date=April 21, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> although Abrams tried to get the chance to direct his own script.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/markets-festivals/par-girding-up-for-war-1117908978/|title=Par girding up for 'War'|first=Michael Fleming, Dave|last=McNary|date=August 12, 2004|access-date=December 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104192428/https://variety.com/2004/film/markets-festivals/par-girding-up-for-war-1117908978/|archive-date=January 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the project was finally cancelled in 2004 and instead  ''[[Superman Returns]]'' was released in 2006.\n\nIn November 2009, it was reported that Abrams and [[Bad Robot Productions]] were producing, along with [[Cartoon Network Movies]], [[Warner Bros.]], [[Frederator Films]] and [[Paramount Pictures]], a [[Samurai Jack (film)|film adaptation]] of ''[[Samurai Jack]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmjunk.com/2009/11/19/j-j-abrams-producing-samurai-jack-the-movie/|title=J.J. Abrams Producing Samurai Jack: The Movie - Film Junk|access-date=July 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704095207/https://filmjunk.com/2009/11/19/j-j-abrams-producing-samurai-jack-the-movie/|archive-date=July 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> However, in June 2012, series creator [[Genndy Tartakovsky]] stated that the production of the film was scrapped after Abrams' departure from the project to direct ''[[Star Trek (2009)|Star Trek]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/727845-a-preview-of-sony-animations-hotel-transylvania|title=A Preview of Sony Animation's Hotel Transylvania - ComingSoon.net|date=June 26, 2012|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030144430/http://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/727845-a-preview-of-sony-animations-hotel-transylvania|archive-date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> For this and other reasons, Tartakovsky decided to make a [[Samurai Jack (season 5)|new season]] instead of a feature film. Also in 2009, it was reported that Abrams and [[Bad Robot Productions]] would produce a film based on the [[Micronauts]] toy line.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125737028160428961|title=The Cry Goes Out in Hollywood: 'Get Me Mr. Potato Head's Agent!'|first=Lauren A. E.|last=Schuker|date=November 6, 2009|via=www.wsj.com|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|access-date=August 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821084527/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125737028160428961|archive-date=August 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theplaylist.blogspot.pe/2009/11/jj-abrams-to-produce-micronauts.html|title=Blogger|website=theplaylist.blogspot.pe}}</ref> However, a film has never gone into production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movies.com/movie-news/39g-i-joe-retaliation39-writers-offer-updates-on-39cowboy-ninja-viking39-39micronauts39-39epsilon39-exclusive/11704|title='G.I. Joe: Retaliation' Writers Offer Updates on 'Cowboy Ninja Viking,' 'Micronauts' and 'Epsilon' (Exclusive) - Movie News - Movies.com|website=Movies.com|access-date=October 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030142213/http://www.movies.com/movie-news/39g-i-joe-retaliation39-writers-offer-updates-on-39cowboy-ninja-viking39-39micronauts39-39epsilon39-exclusive/11704|archive-date=October 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAbrams is married to public relations executive Katie McGrath and has three children.<ref name=college/><ref>[http://alias.unfiction.com/s1/background.htm \"EW Gets the Stories Behind Those Goofy TV Production-Company Logos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717155632/http://alias.unfiction.com/s1/background.htm |date=July 17, 2011 }}, ''Entertainment Weekly'', December 7, 2001: \"The title came to creator J.J. Abrams during a writers' meeting, and he recorded his children, Henry and Gracie (ages 2 and 3), saying the words into his Powerbook's microphone. 'That day in the office while editing,' says Abrams, 'I put together sound effects on my computer, burned a QuickTime movie on a CD, gave it to postproduction, and three days later it was on national television.'\"</ref> He resides in [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles]], California.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/photos.nsf/main/jj_abrams_2072721|title=Jj Abrams, Katie McGrath 4th Annual Pink Party to... \u2013 Picture 2072721|magazine=Contactmusic.com|accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/object/article?f=/g/a/2009/05/06/movie_premieres.DTL&o=2 Director J.J. Abrams and wife, actress Katie \u2013 Media (3 of 46) Movie Premieres: 'Star Trek,' 'Angels] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510144455/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/object/article?f=%2Fg%2Fa%2F2009%2F05%2F06%2Fmovie_premieres.DTL&o=2 |date=May 10, 2009 }}, \"Director J.J. Abrams and wife, actress Katie McGrath, parade on the red carpet as they arrives at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in Hollywood for the premiere of the movie 'Star Trek' in Los Angeles on April 30, 2009.</ref> He is [[Jews|Jewish]] and his wife is Roman Catholic, and he sometimes takes his children to religious services on Jewish holidays.<ref>[http://www.jewishjournal.com/community/article/now_its_jj_abrams_turn_to_trek_20090506/ Jewishjournal.com: Now It's J.J. Abrams' Turn to 'Trek'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222081039/http://www.jewishjournal.com/community/article/now_its_jj_abrams_turn_to_trek_20090506/ |date=December 22, 2015 }}, accessed December 16, 2015</ref>\n\nAbrams serves on the Creative Council of [[Represent.Us]], a [[Nonpartisanism|nonpartisan]] anti-corruption organization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://represent.us/about|title=About {{!}} Represent.Us|newspaper=End corruption. Defend the Republic.|language=en-US|access-date=2016-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023054916/https://represent.us/about/|archive-date=October 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n! colspan=\"3\" |Credited as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n! [[Film director|Director]]\n![[Film producer|Producer]]\n! [[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Taking Care of Business (film)|Taking Care of Business]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Co-writer with Jill Mazursky\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Regarding Henry]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes|Co-Producer}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Forever Young (1992 film)|Forever Young]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes|Executive}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[The Pallbearer]]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Gone Fishin' (film)|Gone Fishin']]''\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n|Co-writer with Jill Mazursky\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Armageddon (