2906216|title=Dungeons & Dragons}}</ref> || [[Paramount Pictures]] / [[Vertigo Entertainment]] / [[Allspark Pictures]] || [[John Francis Daley]], [[Jonathan Goldstein (filmmaker)|Jonathan Goldstein]] (director); Michael Gillio (screenplay) ||<center><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/jonathan-goldstein-john-francis-daley-dungeons-and-dragons-movie-1203285477/|title=Jonathan Goldstein and John Francis Daley in Talks to Direct \u2018Dungeons & Dragons\u2019 Movie|date=July 30, 2019|website=Variety|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| ''[[King Richard (film)|King Richard]]'' || [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] || [[Reinaldo Marcus Green]] (director); Zach Baylin (screenplay); [[Will Smith]], [[Jon Bernthal]], [[Aunjanue Ellis]], [[Saniyya Sidney]], Demi Singleton, [[Liev Schreiber]], [[Dylan McDermott]] ||<center><ref>[https://deadline.com/2020/04/the-batman-sopranos-prequel-tom-elvis-presley-movie-warner-bros-release-dates-changes-coronavirus-1202912605/ \u2018The Batman\u2019 Flies To Fall 2021, \u2018Sopranos\u2019 Prequel Moves To March & More As Warner Bros. Makes Release Date Changes Due To COVID-19 Climate]</ref></center>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center\"| 24\n| ''Gucci'' || [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] || [[Ridley Scott]] (director); Roberto Bentivegna (screenplay); [[Lady Gaga]] ||<center><ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mgm-buys-ridley-scotts-gucci-film-lady-gaga-set-star-1289108? MGM Buys Ridley Scott's 'Gucci' Film With Lady Gaga Set to Star (Exclusive)]</ref></center>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center; background:#87f7bf; textcolor:#000;\" |D<br>E<br>C<br>E<br>M<br>B<br>E<br>R\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 17\n|| ''[[Avatar 2]]'' || [[20th Century Studios]] || [[James Cameron]] (director/screenplay); [[Josh Friedman]] (screenplay); [[Sam Worthington]], [[Zoe Saldana]], [[Stephen Lang]], [[Sigourney Weaver]], [[Giovanni Ribisi]], [[Joel David Moore]], [[Dileep Rao]], [[CCH Pounder]], [[Matt Gerald]], [[Kate Winslet]], [[Cliff Curtis]], [[Michelle Yeoh]], [[Jemaine Clement]], [[David Thewlis]], [[Vin Diesel]] ||<center><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/854041-joel-david-moore-to-reprise-his-role-for-the-avatar-sequels#/slide/1|title=Joel David Moore to Reprise His Role for the Avatar Sequels|date=31 May 2017|publisher=Comingsoon|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 21\n| ''[[Hotel Transylvania (franchise)#Hotel Transylvania 4 (2021)|Hotel Transylvania 4]]'' || [[Columbia Pictures]] / [[Sony Pictures Animation]] || [[Michael McCullers]] (screenplay); [[Adam Sandler]], [[Andy Samberg]], [[Selena Gomez]], [[Kevin James]], [[Fran Drescher]], [[Steve Buscemi]], [[Molly Shannon]], [[Keegan-Michael Key]], [[David Spade]], [[Adam Sandler#Personal life|Sadie Sandler]], [[Asher Blinkoff]], [[Mel Brooks]], [[Kathryn Hahn]] ||<center><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/hotel-transylvania-4-christmas-2021-1202565733/|title='Hotel Transylvania 4' To Open Doors Christmas Season 2021|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=February 26, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=February 26, 2019}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\" | 22\n| ''[[DC Extended Universe#Black Adam (2021)|Black Adam]]'' || [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] / [[New Line Cinema]] / [[DC Films]] || [[Jaume Collet-Serra]] (director); [[Adam Sztykiel]] (screenplay); [[Dwayne Johnson]] ||<center><ref>{{cite web |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |title=Dwayne Johnson Announces 'Black Adam' 2021 Release Date |url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/dwayne-johnson-black-adam-2021-release-date-1202786341/ |website=Deadline |accessdate=November 14, 2019 |date=November 14, 2019}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| ''[[Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows#Sequel|Sherlock Holmes 3]]'' || [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] / [[Village Roadshow Pictures]] / [[Silver Pictures]] || [[Dexter Fletcher]] (director); [[Chris Brancato]] (screenplay); [[Robert Downey Jr.]], [[Jude Law]] ||<center><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/rocketman-dexter-fletcher-sherlock-holmes-3-1203233376/|title='Rocketman's' Dexter Fletcher to Direct 'Sherlock Holmes 3' (EXCLUSIVE)|date=11 July 2019|website=Variety|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| ''[[Sing 2]]'' || [[Universal Pictures]] / [[Illumination (company)|Illumination]] || [[Garth Jennings]] (director/screenplay); [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Reese Witherspoon]], [[Scarlett Johansson]], [[Taron Egerton]], [[Nick Kroll]], [[Tori Kelly]] ||<center><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/minions-rise-gru-lands-new-summer-2021-release-sing-2-wicked-delayed-1287889|title='Minions: Rise of Gru' Lands New Summer 2021 Release; 'Sing 2,' 'Wicked' Delayed|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center\"| 25\n| ''Babylon'' || [[Paramount Pictures]] || [[Damien Chazelle]] (director/screenplay); [[Brad Pitt]] ||<center><ref> [https://variety.com/2019/film/news/paramount-damien-chazelle-babylon-emma-stone-brad-pitt-1203386882/ Paramount Lands Damien Chazelle's 'Babylon' and Dates it for Christmas 2021]</ref></center>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Films of the United States, 2021}}\n* {{imdb country year|us|2021}}\n\n{{portalbar|Film|Lists}}\n{{American films by decade|2020}}\n{{2021 films}}\n{{Filmsbycountry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:American films of 2021}}\n[[Category:Lists of American films by year|2021]]\n[[Category:Lists of 2021 films by country or language|American]]\n", "name_user": "FilmLover72", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril\u2013June:i included a movie that got delayed because of COVID-19", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_American_films_of_2021"}
{"title_page": "Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2010}}\n{{Expand French|Michele Alliot-Marie|topic=gov|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name      = Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]\n| image      = Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, French Minister of Foreign and European Affairs (5277700729) (cropped).jpg\n| office      = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start      = 1 July 2014\n| term_end      =\n| term_start1      = 1 July 1989\n| term_end1      = 22 May 1992\n| constituency1      = [[East France (European Parliament constituency)|East France]]\n| office2      = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (France)|Minister of Foreign and European Affairs]]\n| primeminister2      = [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]\n| term_start2      = 14 November 2010\n| term_end2      = 27 February 2011\n| predecessor2      = [[Bernard Kouchner]]\n| successor2      = [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]]\n| office3      = [[Ministry of Justice (France)|Minister of Justice]]\n| primeminister3      = Fran\u00e7ois Fillon\n| term_start3      = 23 June 2009\n| term_end3      = 13 November 2010\n| predecessor3      = [[Rachida Dati]]\n| successor3      = [[Michel Mercier]]\n| office4      = [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]]\n| primeminister4      = Fran\u00e7ois Fillon\n| term_start4      = 18 May 2007\n| term_end4      = 23 June 2009\n| predecessor4      = [[Fran\u00e7ois Baroin]]\n| successor4      = [[Brice Hortefeux]]\n| office5      = [[Minister of Defence (France)|Minister of Defence]]\n| primeminister5      = {{Ubl|[[Jean-Pierre Raffarin]]|[[Dominique de Villepin]]}}\n| term_start5      = 7 May 2002\n| term_end5      = 18 May 2007\n| predecessor5      = [[Alain Richard]]\n| successor5      = [[Herv\u00e9 Morin]]\n| office6      = [[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports]]\n| primeminister6      = [[\u00c9douard Balladur]]\n| term_start6      = 29 March 1993\n| term_end6      = 18 May 1995\n| predecessor6      = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique Bredin\n| successor6      = [[Guy Drut]]\n| office7      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br />for [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]\n|term_start7      = 16 March 1986\n|term_end7       = 1st May 1993\n|predecessor7      = \n|successor7      = [[Daniel Poulou]]\n|term_start8      = 17 September 1995\n|term_end8       = 18 June 2002\n|predecessor8      = [[Daniel Poulou]]\n|successor8      = [[Daniel Poulou]]\n| birth_name      = Mich\u00e8le Jeanne Honorine Alliot-Marie\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1946|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Villeneuve-le-Roi]], [[France]]\n| death_date      =\n| death_place      =\n| party      = '''''{{flag|France|name=French}}'''''<br />[[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]]<br />'''''{{flag|EU}}'''''<br />[[European People's Party]]\n| otherparty      = [[Rally for the Republic]] (RPR) <small>(before 2002)</small><br />[[Union for a Popular Movement]] (UMP) <small>(2002\u20132015)</small>\n| partner      = [[Patrick Ollier]]\n| children      = 3\n| alma_mater      = {{Ubl|[[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]]|[[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]]}}\n| religion      = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Mich\u00e8le Yvette Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Jeanne Honorine Alliot-Marie''' ({{IPA-fr|mi\u0283\u025bl aljoma\u02c8\u0281i}}; born 10 September 1946), known in France as '''MAM''', is a French [[politician]] and [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) from [[France]]. She is a member of the [[The Republicans (France)|Republicans]], part of the [[European People's Party]]. A member of all right-wing governments formed in the 1980s, 1990s and 2000s, she was the first woman in France to hold the portfolios of [[Minister of Defence (France)|Defense]] (2002\u20132007), [[Minister of the Interior (France)|the Interior]] (2007\u20132009) and [[Ministry of Foreign and European Affairs (France)|Foreign Affairs]] (2010\u20132011);<ref name=\"iht2007\">{{cite news|title=Excerpts From 'Dawn Evening or Night'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/23/world/europe/23iht-23excerpts.7231420.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=New York Times (in the International Herald Tribune)|date=23 August 2007|author=Ariane Bernard (translation)}}</ref> she has also been in charge of [[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Youth and Sports]] (1993\u20131995) and [[Ministry of Justice (France)|Justice]] (2009\u20132010), and was granted the honorary rank of [[Minister of State#France|Minister of State]] in her last two offices.\n\nShe resigned from government in 2011 due to her position during the [[Tunisian Revolution]]; one year later, in the [[2012 French legislative election]]s, she lost her seat as [[National Assembly of France|Deputy]] (MP) for the [[Constituency (France)|6th Constituency]] of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]. She became a [[member of the European Parliament]] in 2014. She remains Deputy Mayor of [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]] as well as Vice President of the National Council of The Republicans.\n\nAlliot-Marie was the last President of the [[Rally for the Republic]] (1999\u20132002), an incarnation of the [[Gaullist party]], and was the first woman to chair a major French political party. She has remained a leading [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] after the RPR merged into the UMP and was seen as a rival to [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] before and after his [[2007 French presidential election|election as President in 2007]], although direct confrontation was always avoided.\n\nAlliot-Marie is a [[law]] and [[political science]] scholar. Her companion is [[Patrick Ollier]], Minister in charge of Relations with Parliament in the Fillon II government; both were ministers simultaneously for a few months in 2010-2011, the first time a couple ever sat in a French government.\n\n== Early life ==\nMich\u00e8le Marie was born on 10 September 1946 in [[Villeneuve-le-Roi]] (then in the [[Seine-et-Oise]] [[Departments of France|department]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Who's Who|newspaper=[[Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9]]|date=25 February 2009|page=2|language=French}}</ref> now in the [[Val-de-Marne]] department since 1968).  Her father is [[Bernard Marie]] (1918-2015), who was a famous international [[Rugby union|rugby]] referee,<ref name=\"galamay2009\">{{cite journal|last=Nedelec|first=Candice|title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie ouvre son jardin secret:  Le ministre de l'Int\u00e8rieur l\u00e8ve le voile sur son intimit\u00e9|journal=Gala|date=9 May 2009|trans-title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie opens her secret garden:  The Minister of Interior unveils her private life|publisher=Prisma Media (then Prisma Presse)|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.gala.fr/l_actu/news_de_stars/michele_alliot-marie_ouvre_son_jardin_secret_178810|Google Translate}}</ref> the [[National Assembly of France|French National Assembly]] [[Deputy (legislator)|Deputy]] for the [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques' 4th constituency]] (1967-1981, department named '''Basses-Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es''' until 1969),<ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la IIIe l\u00e9gislature 1967-1968 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English:  'Alphabetical list of Members of the Third Legislature 1967-1968 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/3/deputes3.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/3/deputes3.asp|Google Translate}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la IVe l\u00e9gislature 1968-1973 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English:  'Alphabetical list of Members of the Fourth Legislature 1968-1973 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/4/deputes4.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/4/deputes4.asp|Google Translate}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la Ve l\u00e9gislature 1973-1978 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English: 'Alphabetical list of Members of the Fifth Legislature 1973-1978 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/5/deputes5.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/5/deputes5.asp|Google Translate}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la VIe l\u00e9gislature 1978-1981 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English: 'Alphabetical list of Members of the Sixth Legislature 1978-1981 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/6/deputes6.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/6/deputes6.asp|Google Translate}}</ref> and the Mayor of [[Biarritz]] (1977-1991);<ref name=\"sudouest\">{{cite news|last=Planes|first=Emmanuel|title=Bernard Marie en premi\u00e8re ligne  (English:  'Bernard Marie in the forward line')|url=http://www.sudouest.fr/2011/02/17/bernard-marie-en-premiere-ligne-320428-652.php|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=[[Sud-Ouest (newspaper)|Sud-Ouest]] (English: 'South-West')|date=17 February 2011|agency=Groupe Sud-Ouest|location=Bordeaux, France|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.sudouest.fr/2011/02/17/bernard-marie-en-premiere-ligne-320428-652.php|Google Translate}}</ref> and her mother is Ren\u00e9e Leyko and is of Polish descent.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[International Who's Who|The International Who's Who 2004]]|year=2003|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=1857432177|author=[[Europa Publications]]}}</ref>\n\nShe attended the High School of the [[Folie Saint James]] in [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]] and then began her studies at the [[Paris Law Faculty]] in the now-defunct [[University of Paris]], continuing at the {{Interlanguage link multi|Paris Arts Faculty|fr|3=Facult\u00e9 des lettres de Paris}} in that same university.  After then-[[Education Minister of France|Education Minister]] [[Edgar Faure]]'s university reforms (known as ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Loi Faure|fr|3=Loi Faure}}'') were implemented in 1968, she continued her studies in [[private law]], [[political science]], and [[legal history]] at both [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Guichoux|first=Marie|title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, 53 ans, fille de famille gaulliste, pr\u00e9sidera peut-\u00eatre le RPR <nowiki>[</nowiki>...<nowiki>]</nowiki>|url=http://www.liberation.fr/portrait/0101301095-michele-alliot-marie-53-ans-fille-de-famille-gaulliste-presidera-peut-etre-le-rpr-samedi-si-le-parti-se-donne-a-une-femme-pour-changer-petite-poigne|newspaper=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|date=4 December 1999|language=French}}</ref> earning a [[Doctor of law|Doctor of Law]] degree there in 1973 with her thesis ''Salari\u00e9 actionnaire'' (English:  \"Employee Shareholders\"), and [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]], where she earned a Doctorate in Political Science in 1982 and defended her thesis ''D\u00e9cisions politiques et structures administratives'' (English:  \"Political Decisions and Administrative Structures\").  During her university years, she was a member of the [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] student union ''[[Union Nationale Inter-universitaire|UNI]]''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Latrous |first1=Neila |last2=Marteau |first2=Jean-Baptiste |title=UMP - un univers impitoyable (English:  'UMP - A Ruthless World') |year=2012 |publisher=Flammarion |location=France |isbn=2081277107 |page=250 |language=French |type=Paperback |chapter=Des jeunes pires que leurs a\u00een\u00e9s (English: 'Young worse than their elders')}}</ref>\n\nShe also holds a ''Certificat d'aptitude \u00e0 la profession d'avocat'' (English:  \"Certificate of Aptitude for Practicing Law\"), also known as a '''CAPA'''; a certificate in [[Africa]]n laws and economics; and a [[Master's degree in Europe|master's degree]] in [[ethnology]].  Before her career in politics, she was a senior lecturer at the [[University of Paris 1 Pantheon-Sorbonne|Paris-I University (Panth\u00e9on-Sorbonne)]], and also spent some time practicing law.  She is also a recipient of the [[Paris Law Faculty|Faculty of Law and Economics]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Biographie de Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie|url=http://www.lechene.org/biographie.html|publisher=Le Ch\u00eane (English:  'The Oak')|accessdate=2 August 2013|language=French}}</ref>\n\n== University, private sector, and early political career ==\nDuring her university studies, Alliot-Marie (then still known as Mich\u00e8le Marie) began having a relationship with her then-law professor {{Interlanguage link multi|Michel Alliot|fr|3=Michel Alliot}}, who was also chief of staff to then-[[Minister of Education (France)|Education Minister]] (1968-1969) [[Edgar Faure]].  Marie and Alliot married in 1971, thus gaining her frequent access to academic and corporate environments; this also led to a name change from Mich\u00e8le Marie to her name since then, Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie.\n\nShe was first assistant at [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]] and then the [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|University Paris I Panth\u00e9on-Sorbonne]] between 1970 and 1984, before becoming a ''[[Academic rank in France#State university system|Ma\u00eetre de conf\u00e9rences]]'' (equal to an Associate Professor) in [[public law]] from 1984, a position she left when she got elected to the [[National Assembly of France|French National Assembly]] in 1986.\n\nIn 1972, she became a technical adviser to [[Edgar Faure]], who was by then the [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Minister of Social Affairs]] until 1976; and then she was a technical adviser to then-Secretary of State for Universities [[Jean-Pierre Soisson]].  She then became an adviser to then-[[Ministry of Overseas France|Minister of Departments and Overseas Territories]] [[Bernard Stasi]] from 1973 to 1974, and then to then-[[Minister of Tourism (France)|Secretary of State for Tourism]] {{Interlanguage link multi|G\u00e9rard Ducray|fr|3=G\u00e9rard Ducray}} in 1974.  She then became the Chief of Staff to then-Secretary of State and Minister of Universities {{Interlanguage link multi|Alice Saunier-Seit\u00e9|fr|3=Alice Saunier-Seit\u00e9}} from 1976 to 1978 before working in the [[private sector]] as an administrator of CEO of the company ''Uta-Indemnit\u00e9'' between 1979 and 1985.<ref>Who's Who in France</ref>  She also practiced as a lawyer during this time.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Local politics ===\nAlliot-Marie started her electoral career in 1983 as Municipal Councillor for the [[French Basque Country|Basque]]-area village of [[Ciboure]] (in the former province of [[Labourd]] and now in the [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] department), located south of her father's political base of [[Biarritz]], near [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]]; she stayed on until 1988.  In 1989, she was elected to another council, this time in Biarritz, alongside her father.  In 1990, as part of the municipal majority behind the first Deputy Mayor [[Didier Borotra]] of the [[Union for French Democracy|UDF]]-[[Centre of Social Democrats|CDS]], she passed draft legislation in opposition to build a hotel-casino on the front of the main beach of the town,<ref name=\"sudouest\" /> which caused a collapse of the council. Early municipal elections in 1991 were won by Didier Borotra, who united the local UDF, two elected [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialists]], and [[Basque nationalism|Basque nationalists]], who provided additional support.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biarritz:  Borotra L'emporte Cantonale dans L'eure |url=https://www.humanite.fr/node/286966 |publisher=L'Humanite |accessdate=2 August 2013 |language=French |date=18 March 1991}}</ref>  She left the council at the same time that her father was defeated as Mayor.  She then served as Mayor of Saint-Jean-de-Luz from 1995 until 2002, and as First Deputy Mayor since then. She was also a member and a Vice President of the General Council of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] between 1994 and 2001.\n\n=== National politics ===\nAlliot-Marie was elected to the [[French National Assembly|National Assembly]] to represent [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] in 1986 as a member of the [[Gaullist]] [[Rally for the Republic]] (RPR). She has been seating in the Assembly ever since, except when she sat in the government; this is due to the French law on ''[[Cumul des mandats]]'' (literally: \"accumulation of mandates\") that prohibit [[Cabinet of France|cabinet ministers]] from simultaneously serving as deputies in the [[National Assembly of France|French National Assembly]]; her [[National Assembly of France#Accumulation of mandates and minimum age|alternate]] as Deputy was [[Daniel Poulou]], who served from 1993 to 1995 and again from 2002 to 2011 when she served as Cabinet Minister.<ref name=\"danielpoulou\">{{cite web|title=Accueil > Archives de la XIIIe l\u00e9gislature > Les d\u00e9put\u00e9s > M. Daniel Poulou (English:  'Home > Archives XIII Legislature > Members > Daniel Poulou')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/2463.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=National Assembly of France|accessdate=2 August 2013|language=French}}</ref>\n\nShe served as Secretary of State (junior minister) for Schools under the [[Minister of National Education (France)|Minister of National Education]] in [[Jacques Chirac]]'s second government from 1986 to 1988 and as [[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports]] in [[\u00c9douard Balladur]]'s government from 1993 to 1995.\n\nFrom 1989 to 1993, she was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] as a member of the [[Political groups of the European Parliament|political group]] [[European Democratic Alliance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mich\u00e8le ALLIOT-MARIE|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/1179/MICHELE_ALLIOT-MARIE_home.html|work=European Parliament / MEPs|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== President of the RPR ===\nIn 1999, \"MAM\" entered the challenge for the presidency of the RPR against Chirac's candidate and, to most insiders' surprise, won by a landslide, becoming the first woman to lead a major French political party. She remained President of the party until 2002 when it merged with the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] (UMP), a merger she opposed at first.\n\n=== Defense ministership ===\n[[File:Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie.jpg|thumb|left|French [[Minister of Defense (France)|Minister of Defense]] Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie meets with US Secretary of Defense [[Donald H. Rumsfeld]] in [[The Pentagon]] on 17 October 2002. Alliot-Marie and Rumsfeld are meeting to discuss defense issues of mutual interest.]]\n\nAlliot-Marie was [[Minister of Defense (France)|Minister of Defense]] during Jacques Chirac\u2019s second presidential term, France's first woman in this position. Between May and June 2002, she was also in charge of [[Minister of Veterans Affairs (France)|Veterans\u2019 Affairs]]. ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine declared her the 57th [[Forbes Magazine's List of The World's 100 Most Powerful Women|most powerful woman in the world]] in 2006<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The World's Most Powerful Women (2006) |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/11/06women_The-100-Most-Powerful-Women_land.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=31 August 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The World's Most Powerful Women (2006) (sorted by rank) |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/11/06women_The-100-Most-Powerful-Women_Rank_3.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=31 August 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Serafin |first=Tatiana |title=The World's Most Powerful Women (2006) > #57 Michele Alliot-Marie |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/11/06women_Michele-Alliot-Marie_04RI.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=31 August 2006}}</ref> and the 11th in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The World's 100 Most Powerful Women (2007) |url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/08/30/most-powerful-women-biz-07women-cz_em_cs_0830power_land.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=30 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The 100 Most Powerful Women (2007) (sorted by rank) |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/11/biz-07women_The-100-Most-Powerful-Women_Rank.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=30 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=MacDonald |first=Elizabeth |title=The 100 Most Powerful Women (2007) > #11 Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/11/biz-07women_Michele-Alliot-Marie_04RI.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=30 August 2007}}</ref>  She kept the Defense portfolio in [[Jean-Pierre Raffarin]]'s three governments and in [[Dominique de Villepin]]'s government.\n\nShe remained a leading Gaullist after the RPR merger into the UMP, and created her own movement within the party, Le Ch\u00eane (The Oak). Although she publicly considered competing with [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] for the UMP nomination in the [[2007 French presidential election|2007 presidential election]], she ruled herself out of the running in January 2007 and endorsed Sarkozy. Sarkozy and Alliot-Marie had a history of disagreements in the party\u2019s National Council.<ref name=\"iht2007\"/>\n\n=== Interior and Justice ministerships ===\nAfter Sarkozy\u2019s election as President, Alliot-Marie was appointed [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior, the Overseas and Local Communities]] in [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]'s government, being the first woman to hold the position.<ref name=\"iht2007\"/>\n\nTwo years later, after the [[2009 European Parliament election in France|2009 European Parliament election]], she was appointed [[Minister of Justice (France)|Minister of Justice and Liberties and Keeper of the Seals]] and was bestowed the title of Minister of State, which gave her the most senior rank in the government after the Prime Minister. She was made a Vice President of the UMP the same year.\n\n=== Foreign Affairs ministership ===\nIn November 2010, Alliot-Marie was appointed Minister of Foreign and European Affairs, remaining Minister of State and being again the first female holder of the office.\n\nWhen [[Tunisian revolution|civil unrest began in Tunisia in early 2011]], Alliot-Marie came under scrutiny for going on vacation there during the events, as she had frequently done in the past. She further caused controversy when she told the National Assembly that French riot police could be offered to help restore order;<ref>Tunisia's troubles: No sign of an end, [[The Economist]], dated 13 January 2011.</ref> she was specifically criticised for allegedly sending [[teargas]] to Tunisia as late as January 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-france-scandal-20110205,0,3337828.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Kim | last=Willsher | date=5 February 2011 | title=France rocked by news of aid to Tunisia and Egypt}}</ref> Before leaving office, she proposed sending [[paratrooper]]s to quell the protests.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Willsher |first=Kim |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-france-scandal-20110205,0,3337828.story |title=Egypt protests: France shaken by news of aid to Tunisia and Egypt |work=Los Angeles Times  |date=4 February 2011 |accessdate=8 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ali |first=Tariq |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-04/egypt-chaos-defines-bleeding-in-despot-arab-world-commentary-by-tariq-ali.html |title=Egypt's Chaos Defines Bleeding in Despotic Arab World: Tariq Ali |publisher=Bloomberg |date=|accessdate=8 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nHer situation embarrassing the government, she resigned as Foreign Minister on 27 February 2011 after only a few months in office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tsr.ch/info/monde/2984680-michele-alliot-marie-jette-l-eponge.html |title=Alain Jupp\u00e9 remplace Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie - rts.ch - info - monde |language=fr |publisher=Tsr.ch |date=2011-02-28 |accessdate=2013-08-18}}</ref> She was succeeded by outgoing Defense Minister and former Prime Minister [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]].\n\nIn the [[2012 French legislative election]]s, she lost her seat as [[National Assembly of France|Deputy]] (MP) for the [[Constituency (France)|6th constituency]] of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] to [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] candidate {{Interlanguage link multi|Sylviane Alaux|fr|3=Sylviane Alaux}} in the second round, 48.38% to Alaux\u2019s 51.62% share of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=R\u00e9sultats des \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives 2012 > Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques - 6\u00e8me circonscription (English:  \"Results of the 2012 Legislative Elections > Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques 6th Constituency\")|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/resultats-elections/legislatives-2012-pyrenees-atlantiques-6eme-circonscription_337928.html|work=L\u00e9gislatives 2012|publisher=L'Express|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the French investigating judge Sabine Kheris requested that the case be referred to the Court of Justice of the Republic [[Dominique de Villepin]], [[Michel Barnier]] and Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie. These former ministers are suspected of having allowed the exfiltration of the mercenaries responsible for the attack on the Bouak\u00e9 camp in 2004, killing nine French soldiers. The operation was allegedly intended to justify a response operation against the [[Laurent Gbagbo]] government in the context of the 2004 crisis in [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/2016/04/BENVENUTO/55185</ref>\n\n=== Political career ===\n\n'''Ministerial offices'''\n\n* Secretary of State for Education: 1986\u20131988.\n* Minister of Youth and Sports: 1993\u20131995.\n* Minister of Defense: 2002\u20132007.\n* Minister of the Interior, Overseas Territories and Territorial Communities : 2007\u20132009.\n* Keeper of the Seals, Minister of State, Minister of Justice and Freedoms: 2009\u20132010.\n* Minister of State, Minister of Foreign and European Affairs: 2010\u20132011 (resignation).\n\n'''Electoral mandates'''\n\n'''''European parliament'''''\n\n* Member of the [[European Parliament]] : 1989-1992 (resignation); since 2014. Elected in 1989, 2014.\n\n'''''National Assembly'''''\n\n* Deputy to the [[National Assembly of France|National Assembly]] for [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] (6th constituency): elected in March 1986 (became minister in March 1986) / 1988\u20131993 / elected in March 1993 (became minister in 1993) / 1995\u20132002 (became minister in 2002) / reelected in 2007 (remained a minister) / 2011-2012 (defeated). Elected in 1986, reelected in 1988, 1993, 1995, 1997, 2002, 2007.\n\n'''''General Council'''''\n\n* Vice President of the General Council of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]: 1994\u20132001.\n* General Councillor of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]: 1994\u20132001.\n\n'''''Municipal Council'''''\n\n* Mayor of [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]]: 1995-2002 (resignation). Reelected in 2001.\n* Deputy Mayor of Saint-Jean-de-Luz : Since 2002. Reelected in 2008.\n* Municipal Councillor of Saint-Jean-de-Luz: since 1995, reelected in 2001, 2008.\n* Municipal Councillor of [[Biarritz]]: 1989\u20131991.\n* Municipal Councillor of [[Ciboure]]: 1983\u20131988.\n\n'''Party political offices'''\n\n* President of the [[Rally for the Republic]]: 1999\u20132002 (party dissolved). Elected in 1999.\n* Vice President of the [[Union for a Popular Movement]]: 2009-2012.\n* Vice President of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] National Council: since 2015.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMich\u00e8le Marie married anthropologist {{Interlanguage link multi|Michel Alliot|fr|3=Michel Alliot}} in 1971, taking the name Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie. They divorced in 1984.\n\nIn the French media, she is nicknamed \"MAM\".\n\nSince 1988, her life partner has been [[Patrick Ollier]], who briefly served as President of the National Assembly in 2007 and subsequently chaired the Assembly\u2019s Economy Committee. In November 2010, he was appointed Minister in charge of Relations with Parliament in the Fillon II government. Both were ministers simultaneously for a few months in 2010-2011, the first time a couple ever sat in a French government. Due to her higher public profile, he has been nicknamed \"Patrick Ollier-Marie\" or \"POM\".\n\n== Decorations and distinctions ==\n\n=== Decorations ===\n* Commander of the Order of the Equatorial Star ([[Gabon]])<ref name=\"decorations\">{{cite web |last=Guiral |first=Antoine |title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie : Ministre de la D\u00e9fense et des Anciens Combattants (English:  'Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, Minister of Defence and Veterans Affairs') |url=http://www.liberation.fr/evenement/0101412153-michele-alliot-marie-ministre-de-la-defense-et-des-anciens-combattants |work=[[Lib\u00e9ration]] |accessdate=3 August 2013 |language=French |date=8 May 2002 |quote=Grande collectionneuse de d\u00e9corations exotiques (commandeur de l'Etoile \u00e9quatoriale du Gabon, du M\u00e9rite de l'Education nationale de C\u00f4te-d'Ivoire ou des Palmes magistrales de 1re classe du P\u00e9rou), elle va d\u00e9sormais pouvoir en distribuer elle-m\u00eame. (English:  'A collector of exotic decorations (Commander of the Equatorial Star of Gabon, Merit National Education Ivory Coast or masterful 1st class Peru Fins), it will now be able to distribute itself.')}}</ref>\n* Commander of the [[Order of the Star of Anjouan]] ([[Comoros]])\n* Commander Order of Merit of National Education ([[C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]]) <ref name=\"decorations\" />\n* Officer of the Order of the Republic ([[Egypt]])\n* ''Palmes magistrales de 1re classe'' ([[Peru]])<ref name=\"decorations\" />\n\n=== Distinctions ===\n* Prix de la r\u00e9v\u00e9lation politique de l'ann\u00e9e (English:  \"Price for Political Revelation of the Year\") 1999 - [[Trombinoscope]] - being elected as President of the [[Rally for the Republic]] party<ref>{{cite web |title=Guigou \u00e9lue \"femme politique de l'ann\u00e9e 1999\". (English:  'Guigou elected \"politician of the year 1999\".') |url=http://www.liberation.fr/politiques/0101322661-guigou-elue-femme-politique-de-l-annee-1999 |work=[[Lib\u00e9ration]] |accessdate=3 August 2013 |language=French |date=26 January 2000}}</ref>\n* Ministre de l'ann\u00e9e (English:  \"Minister of the Year\") 2005 - Trombinoscope\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Biography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Darmon |first=Micha\u00ebl |year=2006 |title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, la grande muette |language=French |trans-title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, the Great Mute |isbn=2-84187-831-7 |publisher=L'Archipel |location=France}}\n\n== Publications ==\n* {{cite thesis |degree=Ph.D. in law |title=Le salari\u00e9 actionnaire |trans-title=Employee Shareholders |language=French |publisher=[[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]] |year=1973}}\n* {{cite thesis |degree=Ph.D. in political science |title=Les D\u00e9cisions politiques et structures administratives |trans-title=Policy Decisions and Administrative Structures |language=French |publisher=[[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Paris I]] |year=1982}}\n* {{cite book |title=La D\u00e9cision politique - Attention ! Une R\u00e9publique peut en cacher une autre |trans-title=Political Decision - Attention! A Republic Can Hide Another |year=1983 |publisher=[[Presses Universitaires de France|PUF]] |location=Paris, France |isbn=2-13-038008-5 |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=La Grande Peur des classes moyennes |trans-title=The Great Fear of the Middle Class |year=1996 |publisher=La table ronde |location=Paris, France |isbn=2-7103-0768-5 |language=French}}\n* {{Cite report |year=1997 |title=Les boursiers \u00e9trangers en France: errements et potentialit\u00e9s |trans-title=Foreign Scholars in France and Potential Mistakes |publisher=Rapport parlementaire au nom de la commission des affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res (English: 'Parliamentary Report on behalf of the Committee on Foreign Affairs') |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=La R\u00e9publique des irresponsables |trans-title=Republic of Irresponsibles |year=1999 |publisher=Odile Jacob |location=France |isbn=2-7381-0727-3 |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=Le Ch\u00eane qu'on rel\u00e8ve |trans-title=The Oak Notes That |year=2005 |publisher=Odile Jacob |location=France |isbn=2-7381-1690-6 |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=Une femme au c\u0153ur du pouvoir d'\u00e9tat |trans-title=A Woman at the Heart of State Power |year=2013 |publisher=[[Plon (publisher)|Plon]] |location=Paris, France |isbn=978-2-259-21824-5 |language=French}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/250.asp Profile at French National Assembly Website] {{machinetranslate|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/250.asp|title=Profile at French National Assembly Website|lang=fr|dlang=en|nolink=y}}\n\n{{commons|Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie|Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique Bredin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports]]|years=1993\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Guy Drut]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Paul Badiola}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]]|years=1995-2002}}\n{{s-aft|after=Pierre (Peyuco) Duhart}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alain Richard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (France)|Minister of Defence]]|years=2002\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Herv\u00e9 Morin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fran\u00e7ois Baroin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brice Hortefeux]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rachida Dati]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Justice (France)|Minister of Justice]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michel Mercier]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bernard Kouchner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (France)|Minister of Foreign and European Affairs]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alain Jupp\u00e9]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nicolas Sarkozy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of [[Rally for the Republic]]|years=1999\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Serge Lepeltier]]<br /><small>Acting</small>}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Fillon I}}\n{{Fillon II}}\n{{Foreign Ministers of France}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alliot-Marie, Michele}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Villeneuve-le-Roi]]\n[[Category:French people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Rally for the Republic politicians]]\n[[Category:Union for a Popular Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Gaullism, a way forward for France]]\n[[Category:French Foreign Ministers]]\n[[Category:French interior ministers]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Defence]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Justice]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Overseas France]]\n[[Category:MEPs for South-West France 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in France]]\n[[Category:Female defence ministers]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Panth\u00e9on-Assas University alumni]]\n[[Category:The Republicans (France) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of France]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 13th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Female justice ministers]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for France]]\n[[Category:French women diplomats]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2010}}\n{{Expand French|Michele Alliot-Marie|topic=gov|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name      = Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]\n| image      = Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, French Minister of Foreign and European Affairs (5277700729) (cropped).jpg\n| office      = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start      = 1 July 2014\n| term_end      =\n| term_start1      = 1 July 1989\n| term_end1      = 22 May 1992\n| constituency1      = [[East France (European Parliament constituency)|East France]]\n| office2      = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (France)|Minister of Foreign and European Affairs]]\n| primeminister2      = [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]\n| term_start2      = 14 November 2010\n| term_end2      = 27 February 2011\n| predecessor2      = [[Bernard Kouchner]]\n| successor2      = [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]]\n| office3      = [[Ministry of Justice (France)|Minister of Justice]]\n| primeminister3      = Fran\u00e7ois Fillon\n| term_start3      = 23 June 2009\n| term_end3      = 13 November 2010\n| predecessor3      = [[Rachida Dati]]\n| successor3      = [[Michel Mercier]]\n| office4      = [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]]\n| primeminister4      = Fran\u00e7ois Fillon\n| term_start4      = 18 May 2007\n| term_end4      = 23 June 2009\n| predecessor4      = [[Fran\u00e7ois Baroin]]\n| successor4      = [[Brice Hortefeux]]\n| office5      = [[Minister of Defence (France)|Minister of Defence]]\n| primeminister5      = {{Ubl|[[Jean-Pierre Raffarin]]|[[Dominique de Villepin]]}}\n| term_start5      = 7 May 2002\n| term_end5      = 18 May 2007\n| predecessor5      = [[Alain Richard]]\n| successor5      = [[Herv\u00e9 Morin]]\n| office6      = [[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports]]\n| primeminister6      = [[\u00c9douard Balladur]]\n| term_start6      = 29 March 1993\n| term_end6      = 18 May 1995\n| predecessor6      = Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique Bredin\n| successor6      = [[Guy Drut]]\n| office7      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br />for [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]\n|term_start7      = 16 March 1986\n|term_end7       = 1st May 1993\n|predecessor7      = \n|successor7      = [[Daniel Poulou]]\n|term_start8      = 17 September 1995\n|term_end8       = 18 June 2002\n|predecessor8      = [[Daniel Poulou]]\n|successor8      = [[Daniel Poulou]]\n| birth_name      = Mich\u00e8le Jeanne Honorine Alliot-Marie\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1946|9|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Villeneuve-le-Roi]], [[France]]\n| death_date      =\n| death_place      =\n| party      = '''''{{flag|France|name=French}}'''''<br />[[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]]<br />'''''{{flag|EU}}'''''<br />[[European People's Party]]\n| otherparty      = [[Rally for the Republic]] (RPR) <small>(before 2002)</small><br />[[Union for a Popular Movement]] (UMP) <small>(2002\u20132015)</small>\n| partner      = [[Patrick Ollier]]\n| children      = 3\n| alma_mater      = {{Ubl|[[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]]|[[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]]}}\n| religion      = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| website      =\n}}\n\n'''Mich\u00e8le Yvette Marie-Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Jeanne Honorine Alliot-Marie''' ({{IPA-fr|mi\u0283\u025bl aljoma\u02c8\u0281i}}; born 10 September 1946), known in France as '''MAM''', is a French [[politician]] and [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) from [[France]]. She is a member of the [[The Republicans (France)|Republicans]], part of the [[European People's Party]]. A member of all right-wing governments formed in the 1980s, 1990s and 2000s, she was the first woman in France to hold the portfolios of [[Minister of Defence (France)|Defense]] (2002\u20132007), [[Minister of the Interior (France)|the Interior]] (2007\u20132009) and [[Ministry of Foreign and European Affairs (France)|Foreign Affairs]] (2010\u20132011).;<ref name=\"iht2007\">{{cite news|title=Excerpts From 'Dawn Evening or Night'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/23/world/europe/23iht-23excerpts.7231420.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=New York Times (in the International Herald Tribune)|date=23 August 2007|author=Ariane Bernard (translation)}}</ref> she has also been in charge of [[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Youth and Sports]] (1993\u20131995) and [[Ministry of Justice (France)|Justice]] (2009\u20132010), and was granted the honorary rank of [[Minister of State#France|Minister of State]] in her last two offices.\n\nShe resigned from government in 2011 due to her position during the [[Tunisian Revolution]]; one year later, in the [[2012 French legislative election]]s, she lost her seat as [[National Assembly of France|Deputy]] (MP) for the [[Constituency (France)|6th Constituency]] of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]. She became a [[member of the European Parliament]] in 2014. She remains Deputy Mayor of [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]] as well as Vice President of the National Council of The Republicans.\n\nAlliot-Marie was the last President of the [[Rally for the Republic]] (1999\u20132002), an incarnation of the [[Gaullist party]], and was the first woman to chair a major French political party. She has remained a leading [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] after the RPR merged into the UMP and was seen as a rival to [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] before and after his [[2007 French presidential election|election as President in 2007]], although direct confrontation was always avoided.\n\nAlliot-Marie is a [[law]] and [[political science]] scholar. Her companion is [[Patrick Ollier]], Minister in charge of Relations with Parliament in the Fillon II government; both were ministers simultaneously for a few months in 2010-2011, the first time a couple ever sat in a French government.\n\n== Early life ==\nMich\u00e8le Marie was born on 10 September 1946 in [[Villeneuve-le-Roi]] (then in the [[Seine-et-Oise]] [[Departments of France|department]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Who's Who|newspaper=[[Le Canard encha\u00een\u00e9]]|date=25 February 2009|page=2|language=French}}</ref> now in the [[Val-de-Marne]] department since 1968).  Her father is [[Bernard Marie]] (1918-2015), who was a famous international [[Rugby union|rugby]] referee,<ref name=\"galamay2009\">{{cite journal|last=Nedelec|first=Candice|title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie ouvre son jardin secret:  Le ministre de l'Int\u00e8rieur l\u00e8ve le voile sur son intimit\u00e9|journal=Gala|date=9 May 2009|trans-title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie opens her secret garden:  The Minister of Interior unveils her private life|publisher=Prisma Media (then Prisma Presse)|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.gala.fr/l_actu/news_de_stars/michele_alliot-marie_ouvre_son_jardin_secret_178810|Google Translate}}</ref> the [[National Assembly of France|French National Assembly]] [[Deputy (legislator)|Deputy]] for the [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques' 4th constituency]] (1967-1981, department named '''Basses-Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es''' until 1969),<ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la IIIe l\u00e9gislature 1967-1968 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English:  'Alphabetical list of Members of the Third Legislature 1967-1968 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/3/deputes3.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/3/deputes3.asp|Google Translate}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la IVe l\u00e9gislature 1968-1973 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English:  'Alphabetical list of Members of the Fourth Legislature 1968-1973 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/4/deputes4.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/4/deputes4.asp|Google Translate}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la Ve l\u00e9gislature 1973-1978 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English: 'Alphabetical list of Members of the Fifth Legislature 1973-1978 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/5/deputes5.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/5/deputes5.asp|Google Translate}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Liste alphab\u00e9tique des d\u00e9put\u00e9s de la VIe l\u00e9gislature 1978-1981 (groupe politique, d\u00e9partement) (English: 'Alphabetical list of Members of the Sixth Legislature 1978-1981 (Political group, department)')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/6/deputes6.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=[[French National Assembly]] official website|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/6/deputes6.asp|Google Translate}}</ref> and the Mayor of [[Biarritz]] (1977-1991);<ref name=\"sudouest\">{{cite news|last=Planes|first=Emmanuel|title=Bernard Marie en premi\u00e8re ligne  (English:  'Bernard Marie in the forward line')|url=http://www.sudouest.fr/2011/02/17/bernard-marie-en-premiere-ligne-320428-652.php|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=[[Sud-Ouest (newspaper)|Sud-Ouest]] (English: 'South-West')|date=17 February 2011|agency=Groupe Sud-Ouest|location=Bordeaux, France|language=French}} {{Google translation|en|fr|http://www.sudouest.fr/2011/02/17/bernard-marie-en-premiere-ligne-320428-652.php|Google Translate}}</ref> and her mother is Ren\u00e9e Leyko and is of Polish descent.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[International Who's Who|The International Who's Who 2004]]|year=2003|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=1857432177|author=[[Europa Publications]]}}</ref>\n\nShe attended the High School of the [[Folie Saint James]] in [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]] and then began her studies at the [[Paris Law Faculty]] in the now-defunct [[University of Paris]], continuing at the {{Interlanguage link multi|Paris Arts Faculty|fr|3=Facult\u00e9 des lettres de Paris}} in that same university.  After then-[[Education Minister of France|Education Minister]] [[Edgar Faure]]'s university reforms (known as ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Loi Faure|fr|3=Loi Faure}}'') were implemented in 1968, she continued her studies in [[private law]], [[political science]], and [[legal history]] at both [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Guichoux|first=Marie|title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, 53 ans, fille de famille gaulliste, pr\u00e9sidera peut-\u00eatre le RPR <nowiki>[</nowiki>...<nowiki>]</nowiki>|url=http://www.liberation.fr/portrait/0101301095-michele-alliot-marie-53-ans-fille-de-famille-gaulliste-presidera-peut-etre-le-rpr-samedi-si-le-parti-se-donne-a-une-femme-pour-changer-petite-poigne|newspaper=[[Lib\u00e9ration]]|date=4 December 1999|language=French}}</ref> earning a [[Doctor of law|Doctor of Law]] degree there in 1973 with her thesis ''Salari\u00e9 actionnaire'' (English:  \"Employee Shareholders\"), and [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University]], where she earned a Doctorate in Political Science in 1982 and defended her thesis ''D\u00e9cisions politiques et structures administratives'' (English:  \"Political Decisions and Administrative Structures\").  During her university years, she was a member of the [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] student union ''[[Union Nationale Inter-universitaire|UNI]]''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Latrous |first1=Neila |last2=Marteau |first2=Jean-Baptiste |title=UMP - un univers impitoyable (English:  'UMP - A Ruthless World') |year=2012 |publisher=Flammarion |location=France |isbn=2081277107 |page=250 |language=French |type=Paperback |chapter=Des jeunes pires que leurs a\u00een\u00e9s (English: 'Young worse than their elders')}}</ref>\n\nShe also holds a ''Certificat d'aptitude \u00e0 la profession d'avocat'' (English:  \"Certificate of Aptitude for Practicing Law\"), also known as a '''CAPA'''; a certificate in [[Africa]]n laws and economics; and a [[Master's degree in Europe|master's degree]] in [[ethnology]].  Before her career in politics, she was a senior lecturer at the [[University of Paris 1 Pantheon-Sorbonne|Paris-I University (Panth\u00e9on-Sorbonne)]], and also spent some time practicing law.  She is also a recipient of the [[Paris Law Faculty|Faculty of Law and Economics]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Biographie de Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie|url=http://www.lechene.org/biographie.html|publisher=Le Ch\u00eane (English:  'The Oak')|accessdate=2 August 2013|language=French}}</ref>\n\n== University, private sector, and early political career ==\nDuring her university studies, Alliot-Marie (then still known as Mich\u00e8le Marie) began having a relationship with her then-law professor {{Interlanguage link multi|Michel Alliot|fr|3=Michel Alliot}}, who was also chief of staff to then-[[Minister of Education (France)|Education Minister]] (1968-1969) [[Edgar Faure]].  Marie and Alliot married in 1971, thus gaining her frequent access to academic and corporate environments; this also led to a name change from Mich\u00e8le Marie to her name since then, Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie.\n\nShe was first assistant at [[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]] and then the [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|University Paris I Panth\u00e9on-Sorbonne]] between 1970 and 1984, before becoming a ''[[Academic rank in France#State university system|Ma\u00eetre de conf\u00e9rences]]'' (equal to an Associate Professor) in [[public law]] from 1984, a position she left when she got elected to the [[National Assembly of France|French National Assembly]] in 1986.\n\nIn 1972, she became a technical adviser to [[Edgar Faure]], who was by then the [[Minister of Social Affairs (France)|Minister of Social Affairs]] until 1976; and then she was a technical adviser to then-Secretary of State for Universities [[Jean-Pierre Soisson]].  She then became an adviser to then-[[Ministry of Overseas France|Minister of Departments and Overseas Territories]] [[Bernard Stasi]] from 1973 to 1974, and then to then-[[Minister of Tourism (France)|Secretary of State for Tourism]] {{Interlanguage link multi|G\u00e9rard Ducray|fr|3=G\u00e9rard Ducray}} in 1974.  She then became the Chief of Staff to then-Secretary of State and Minister of Universities {{Interlanguage link multi|Alice Saunier-Seit\u00e9|fr|3=Alice Saunier-Seit\u00e9}} from 1976 to 1978 before working in the [[private sector]] as an administrator of CEO of the company ''Uta-Indemnit\u00e9'' between 1979 and 1985.<ref>Who's Who in France</ref>  She also practiced as a lawyer during this time.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Local politics ===\nAlliot-Marie started her electoral career in 1983 as Municipal Councillor for the [[French Basque Country|Basque]]-area village of [[Ciboure]] (in the former province of [[Labourd]] and now in the [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] department), located south of her father's political base of [[Biarritz]], near [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]]; she stayed on until 1988.  In 1989, she was elected to another council, this time in Biarritz, alongside her father.  In 1990, as part of the municipal majority behind the first Deputy Mayor [[Didier Borotra]] of the [[Union for French Democracy|UDF]]-[[Centre of Social Democrats|CDS]], she passed draft legislation in opposition to build a hotel-casino on the front of the main beach of the town,<ref name=\"sudouest\" /> which caused a collapse of the council. Early municipal elections in 1991 were won by Didier Borotra, who united the local UDF, two elected [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialists]], and [[Basque nationalism|Basque nationalists]], who provided additional support.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biarritz:  Borotra L'emporte Cantonale dans L'eure |url=https://www.humanite.fr/node/286966 |publisher=L'Humanite |accessdate=2 August 2013 |language=French |date=18 March 1991}}</ref>  She left the council at the same time that her father was defeated as Mayor.  She then served as Mayor of Saint-Jean-de-Luz from 1995 until 2002, and as First Deputy Mayor since then. She was also a member and a Vice President of the General Council of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] between 1994 and 2001.\n\n=== National politics ===\nAlliot-Marie was elected to the [[French National Assembly|National Assembly]] to represent [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] in 1986 as a member of the [[Gaullist]] [[Rally for the Republic]] (RPR). She has been seating in the Assembly ever since, except when she sat in the government; this is due to the French law on ''[[Cumul des mandats]]'' (literally: \"accumulation of mandates\") that prohibit [[Cabinet of France|cabinet ministers]] from simultaneously serving as deputies in the [[National Assembly of France|French National Assembly]]; her [[National Assembly of France#Accumulation of mandates and minimum age|alternate]] as Deputy was [[Daniel Poulou]], who served from 1993 to 1995 and again from 2002 to 2011 when she served as Cabinet Minister.<ref name=\"danielpoulou\">{{cite web|title=Accueil > Archives de la XIIIe l\u00e9gislature > Les d\u00e9put\u00e9s > M. Daniel Poulou (English:  'Home > Archives XIII Legislature > Members > Daniel Poulou')|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/2463.asp|work=Assembl\u00e9e nationale|publisher=National Assembly of France|accessdate=2 August 2013|language=French}}</ref>\n\nShe served as Secretary of State (junior minister) for Schools under the [[Minister of National Education (France)|Minister of National Education]] in [[Jacques Chirac]]'s second government from 1986 to 1988 and as [[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports]] in [[\u00c9douard Balladur]]'s government from 1993 to 1995.\n\nFrom 1989 to 1993, she was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] as a member of the [[Political groups of the European Parliament|political group]] [[European Democratic Alliance]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mich\u00e8le ALLIOT-MARIE|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/1179/MICHELE_ALLIOT-MARIE_home.html|work=European Parliament / MEPs|accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== President of the RPR ===\nIn 1999, \"MAM\" entered the challenge for the presidency of the RPR against Chirac's candidate and, to most insiders' surprise, won by a landslide, becoming the first woman to lead a major French political party. She remained President of the party until 2002 when it merged with the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] (UMP), a merger she opposed at first.\n\n=== Defense ministership ===\n[[File:Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie.jpg|thumb|left|French [[Minister of Defense (France)|Minister of Defense]] Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie meets with US Secretary of Defense [[Donald H. Rumsfeld]] in [[The Pentagon]] on 17 October 2002. Alliot-Marie and Rumsfeld are meeting to discuss defense issues of mutual interest.]]\n\nAlliot-Marie was [[Minister of Defense (France)|Minister of Defense]] during Jacques Chirac\u2019s second presidential term, France's first woman in this position. Between May and June 2002, she was also in charge of [[Minister of Veterans Affairs (France)|Veterans\u2019 Affairs]]. ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine declared her the 57th [[Forbes Magazine's List of The World's 100 Most Powerful Women|most powerful woman in the world]] in 2006<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The World's Most Powerful Women (2006) |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/11/06women_The-100-Most-Powerful-Women_land.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=31 August 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The World's Most Powerful Women (2006) (sorted by rank) |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/11/06women_The-100-Most-Powerful-Women_Rank_3.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=31 August 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Serafin |first=Tatiana |title=The World's Most Powerful Women (2006) > #57 Michele Alliot-Marie |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/11/06women_Michele-Alliot-Marie_04RI.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=31 August 2006}}</ref> and the 11th in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The World's 100 Most Powerful Women (2007) |url=https://www.forbes.com/2007/08/30/most-powerful-women-biz-07women-cz_em_cs_0830power_land.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=30 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=MacDonald |first1=Elizabeth |last2=Schoenberger |first2=Chana R. |title=The 100 Most Powerful Women (2007) (sorted by rank) |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/11/biz-07women_The-100-Most-Powerful-Women_Rank.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=30 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=MacDonald |first=Elizabeth |title=The 100 Most Powerful Women (2007) > #11 Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2007/11/biz-07women_Michele-Alliot-Marie_04RI.html |work=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]] |publisher=Forbes publishing |accessdate=2 August 2013 |date=30 August 2007}}</ref>  She kept the Defense portfolio in [[Jean-Pierre Raffarin]]'s three governments and in [[Dominique de Villepin]]'s government.\n\nShe remained a leading Gaullist after the RPR merger into the UMP, and created her own movement within the party, Le Ch\u00eane (The Oak). Although she publicly considered competing with [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] for the UMP nomination in the [[2007 French presidential election|2007 presidential election]], she ruled herself out of the running in January 2007 and endorsed Sarkozy. Sarkozy and Alliot-Marie had a history of disagreements in the party\u2019s National Council.<ref name=\"iht2007\"/>\n\n=== Interior and Justice ministerships ===\nAfter Sarkozy\u2019s election as President, Alliot-Marie was appointed [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior, the Overseas and Local Communities]] in [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]]'s government, being the first woman to hold the position.<ref name=\"iht2007\"/>\n\nTwo years later, after the [[2009 European Parliament election in France|2009 European Parliament election]], she was appointed [[Minister of Justice (France)|Minister of Justice and Liberties and Keeper of the Seals]] and was bestowed the title of Minister of State, which gave her the most senior rank in the government after the Prime Minister. She was made a Vice President of the UMP the same year.\n\n=== Foreign Affairs ministership ===\nIn November 2010, Alliot-Marie was appointed Minister of Foreign and European Affairs, remaining Minister of State and being again the first female holder of the office.\n\nWhen [[Tunisian revolution|civil unrest began in Tunisia in early 2011]], Alliot-Marie came under scrutiny for going on vacation there during the events, as she had frequently done in the past. She further caused controversy when she told the National Assembly that French riot police could be offered to help restore order;<ref>Tunisia's troubles: No sign of an end, [[The Economist]], dated 13 January 2011.</ref> she was specifically criticised for allegedly sending [[teargas]] to Tunisia as late as January 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-france-scandal-20110205,0,3337828.story | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Kim | last=Willsher | date=5 February 2011 | title=France rocked by news of aid to Tunisia and Egypt}}</ref> Before leaving office, she proposed sending [[paratrooper]]s to quell the protests.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Willsher |first=Kim |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-france-scandal-20110205,0,3337828.story |title=Egypt protests: France shaken by news of aid to Tunisia and Egypt |work=Los Angeles Times  |date=4 February 2011 |accessdate=8 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ali |first=Tariq |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-04/egypt-chaos-defines-bleeding-in-despot-arab-world-commentary-by-tariq-ali.html |title=Egypt's Chaos Defines Bleeding in Despotic Arab World: Tariq Ali |publisher=Bloomberg |date=|accessdate=8 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nHer situation embarrassing the government, she resigned as Foreign Minister on 27 February 2011 after only a few months in office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tsr.ch/info/monde/2984680-michele-alliot-marie-jette-l-eponge.html |title=Alain Jupp\u00e9 remplace Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie - rts.ch - info - monde |language=fr |publisher=Tsr.ch |date=2011-02-28 |accessdate=2013-08-18}}</ref> She was succeeded by outgoing Defense Minister and former Prime Minister [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]].\n\nIn the [[2012 French legislative election]]s, she lost her seat as [[National Assembly of France|Deputy]] (MP) for the [[Constituency (France)|6th constituency]] of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] to [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]] candidate {{Interlanguage link multi|Sylviane Alaux|fr|3=Sylviane Alaux}} in the second round, 48.38% to Alaux\u2019s 51.62% share of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=R\u00e9sultats des \u00e9lections l\u00e9gislatives 2012 > Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques - 6\u00e8me circonscription (English:  \"Results of the 2012 Legislative Elections > Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques 6th Constituency\")|url=http://www.lexpress.fr/resultats-elections/legislatives-2012-pyrenees-atlantiques-6eme-circonscription_337928.html|work=L\u00e9gislatives 2012|publisher=L'Express|accessdate=1 August 2013|language=French|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the French investigating judge Sabine Kheris requested that the case be referred to the Court of Justice of the Republic [[Dominique de Villepin]], [[Michel Barnier]] and Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie. These former ministers are suspected of having allowed the exfiltration of the mercenaries responsible for the attack on the Bouak\u00e9 camp in 2004, killing nine French soldiers. The operation was allegedly intended to justify a response operation against the [[Laurent Gbagbo]] government in the context of the 2004 crisis in [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>https://www.monde-diplomatique.fr/2016/04/BENVENUTO/55185</ref>\n\n=== Political career ===\n\n'''Ministerial offices'''\n\n* Secretary of State for Education: 1986\u20131988.\n* Minister of Youth and Sports: 1993\u20131995.\n* Minister of Defense: 2002\u20132007.\n* Minister of the Interior, Overseas Territories and Territorial Communities : 2007\u20132009.\n* Keeper of the Seals, Minister of State, Minister of Justice and Freedoms: 2009\u20132010.\n* Minister of State, Minister of Foreign and European Affairs: 2010\u20132011 (resignation).\n\n'''Electoral mandates'''\n\n'''''European parliament'''''\n\n* Member of the [[European Parliament]] : 1989-1992 (resignation); since 2014. Elected in 1989, 2014.\n\n'''''National Assembly'''''\n\n* Deputy to the [[National Assembly of France|National Assembly]] for [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]] (6th constituency): elected in March 1986 (became minister in March 1986) / 1988\u20131993 / elected in March 1993 (became minister in 1993) / 1995\u20132002 (became minister in 2002) / reelected in 2007 (remained a minister) / 2011-2012 (defeated). Elected in 1986, reelected in 1988, 1993, 1995, 1997, 2002, 2007.\n\n'''''General Council'''''\n\n* Vice President of the General Council of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]: 1994\u20132001.\n* General Councillor of [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques]]: 1994\u20132001.\n\n'''''Municipal Council'''''\n\n* Mayor of [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]]: 1995-2002 (resignation). Reelected in 2001.\n* Deputy Mayor of Saint-Jean-de-Luz : Since 2002. Reelected in 2008.\n* Municipal Councillor of Saint-Jean-de-Luz: since 1995, reelected in 2001, 2008.\n* Municipal Councillor of [[Biarritz]]: 1989\u20131991.\n* Municipal Councillor of [[Ciboure]]: 1983\u20131988.\n\n'''Party political offices'''\n\n* President of the [[Rally for the Republic]]: 1999\u20132002 (party dissolved). Elected in 1999.\n* Vice President of the [[Union for a Popular Movement]]: 2009-2012.\n* Vice President of [[The Republicans (France)|The Republicans]] National Council: since 2015.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMich\u00e8le Marie married anthropologist {{Interlanguage link multi|Michel Alliot|fr|3=Michel Alliot}} in 1971, taking the name Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie. They divorced in 1984.\n\nIn the French media, she is nicknamed \"MAM\".\n\nSince 1988, her life partner has been [[Patrick Ollier]], who briefly served as President of the National Assembly in 2007 and subsequently chaired the Assembly\u2019s Economy Committee. In November 2010, he was appointed Minister in charge of Relations with Parliament in the Fillon II government. Both were ministers simultaneously for a few months in 2010-2011, the first time a couple ever sat in a French government. Due to her higher public profile, he has been nicknamed \"Patrick Ollier-Marie\" or \"POM\".\n\n== Decorations and distinctions ==\n\n=== Decorations ===\n* Commander of the Order of the Equatorial Star ([[Gabon]])<ref name=\"decorations\">{{cite web |last=Guiral |first=Antoine |title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie : Ministre de la D\u00e9fense et des Anciens Combattants (English:  'Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, Minister of Defence and Veterans Affairs') |url=http://www.liberation.fr/evenement/0101412153-michele-alliot-marie-ministre-de-la-defense-et-des-anciens-combattants |work=[[Lib\u00e9ration]] |accessdate=3 August 2013 |language=French |date=8 May 2002 |quote=Grande collectionneuse de d\u00e9corations exotiques (commandeur de l'Etoile \u00e9quatoriale du Gabon, du M\u00e9rite de l'Education nationale de C\u00f4te-d'Ivoire ou des Palmes magistrales de 1re classe du P\u00e9rou), elle va d\u00e9sormais pouvoir en distribuer elle-m\u00eame. (English:  'A collector of exotic decorations (Commander of the Equatorial Star of Gabon, Merit National Education Ivory Coast or masterful 1st class Peru Fins), it will now be able to distribute itself.')}}</ref>\n* Commander of the [[Order of the Star of Anjouan]] ([[Comoros]])\n* Commander Order of Merit of National Education ([[C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]]) <ref name=\"decorations\" />\n* Officer of the Order of the Republic ([[Egypt]])\n* ''Palmes magistrales de 1re classe'' ([[Peru]])<ref name=\"decorations\" />\n\n=== Distinctions ===\n* Prix de la r\u00e9v\u00e9lation politique de l'ann\u00e9e (English:  \"Price for Political Revelation of the Year\") 1999 - [[Trombinoscope]] - being elected as President of the [[Rally for the Republic]] party<ref>{{cite web |title=Guigou \u00e9lue \"femme politique de l'ann\u00e9e 1999\". (English:  'Guigou elected \"politician of the year 1999\".') |url=http://www.liberation.fr/politiques/0101322661-guigou-elue-femme-politique-de-l-annee-1999 |work=[[Lib\u00e9ration]] |accessdate=3 August 2013 |language=French |date=26 January 2000}}</ref>\n* Ministre de l'ann\u00e9e (English:  \"Minister of the Year\") 2005 - Trombinoscope\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Biography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Darmon |first=Micha\u00ebl |year=2006 |title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, la grande muette |language=French |trans-title=Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie, the Great Mute |isbn=2-84187-831-7 |publisher=L'Archipel |location=France}}\n\n== Publications ==\n* {{cite thesis |degree=Ph.D. in law |title=Le salari\u00e9 actionnaire |trans-title=Employee Shareholders |language=French |publisher=[[Panth\u00e9on-Assas University]] |year=1973}}\n* {{cite thesis |degree=Ph.D. in political science |title=Les D\u00e9cisions politiques et structures administratives |trans-title=Policy Decisions and Administrative Structures |language=French |publisher=[[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Paris I]] |year=1982}}\n* {{cite book |title=La D\u00e9cision politique - Attention ! Une R\u00e9publique peut en cacher une autre |trans-title=Political Decision - Attention! A Republic Can Hide Another |year=1983 |publisher=[[Presses Universitaires de France|PUF]] |location=Paris, France |isbn=2-13-038008-5 |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=La Grande Peur des classes moyennes |trans-title=The Great Fear of the Middle Class |year=1996 |publisher=La table ronde |location=Paris, France |isbn=2-7103-0768-5 |language=French}}\n* {{Cite report |year=1997 |title=Les boursiers \u00e9trangers en France: errements et potentialit\u00e9s |trans-title=Foreign Scholars in France and Potential Mistakes |publisher=Rapport parlementaire au nom de la commission des affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res (English: 'Parliamentary Report on behalf of the Committee on Foreign Affairs') |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=La R\u00e9publique des irresponsables |trans-title=Republic of Irresponsibles |year=1999 |publisher=Odile Jacob |location=France |isbn=2-7381-0727-3 |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=Le Ch\u00eane qu'on rel\u00e8ve |trans-title=The Oak Notes That |year=2005 |publisher=Odile Jacob |location=France |isbn=2-7381-1690-6 |language=French}}\n* {{cite book |title=Une femme au c\u0153ur du pouvoir d'\u00e9tat |trans-title=A Woman at the Heart of State Power |year=2013 |publisher=[[Plon (publisher)|Plon]] |location=Paris, France |isbn=978-2-259-21824-5 |language=French}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/250.asp Profile at French National Assembly Website] {{machinetranslate|url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/250.asp|title=Profile at French National Assembly Website|lang=fr|dlang=en|nolink=y}}\n\n{{commons|Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie|Mich\u00e8le Alliot-Marie}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique Bredin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports (France)|Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports]]|years=1993\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Guy Drut]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=Paul Badiola}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Mayor of [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]]|years=1995-2002}}\n{{s-aft|after=Pierre (Peyuco) Duhart}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alain Richard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (France)|Minister of Defence]]|years=2002\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Herv\u00e9 Morin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Fran\u00e7ois Baroin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minister of the Interior]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brice Hortefeux]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rachida Dati]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Justice (France)|Minister of Justice]]|years=2009\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michel Mercier]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bernard Kouchner]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (France)|Minister of Foreign and European Affairs]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alain Jupp\u00e9]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nicolas Sarkozy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of [[Rally for the Republic]]|years=1999\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Serge Lepeltier]]<br /><small>Acting</small>}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Fillon I}}\n{{Fillon II}}\n{{Foreign Ministers of France}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alliot-Marie, Michele}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Villeneuve-le-Roi]]\n[[Category:French people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Rally for the Republic politicians]]\n[[Category:Union for a Popular Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Gaullism, a way forward for France]]\n[[Category:French Foreign Ministers]]\n[[Category:French interior ministers]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Defence]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Justice]]\n[[Category:French Ministers of Overseas France]]\n[[Category:MEPs for South-West France 2014\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in France]]\n[[Category:Female defence ministers]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Panth\u00e9on-Assas University alumni]]\n[[Category:The Republicans (France) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of France]]\n[[Category:20th-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 13th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Female justice ministers]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for France]]\n[[Category:French women diplomats]]\n", "name_user": "Arms & Hearts", "label": "safe", "comment": "punc", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mich%C3%A8le_Alliot-Marie"}
{"title_page": "List of directly imaged exoplanets", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:HR 8799 Orbiting Exoplanets.gif|thumb|right|Motion interpolation of seven images of the [[HR 8799]] system taken from the [[W. M. Keck Observatory]] over seven years, featuring four [[exoplanet]]s]]\nThis is a '''list of [[extrasolar planet]]s that have been [[Methods of detecting extrasolar planets#Direct imaging|directly observed]]''', sorted by observed separations. This method works best for young planets that emit infrared light and are far from the glare of the star.  Currently, this list includes both directly imaged planets and imaged planetary-mass companions (objects that orbit a star but formed through a binary-star-formation process, not a planet-formation process). This list does not include free-floating planetary-mass objects in star-forming regions or young associations, which are also referred to as [[rogue planet]]s.\n\nThe data given for each planet is taken from the latest published paper on the planet to have that data. In many cases it is not possible to have an exact value, and an estimated range is instead provided. The least massive planet is [[Fomalhaut b]], which has a mass of 2 M<sub>J</sub> or less. The coldest and oldest is [[59 Virginis b]] with a mean temperature of 240&nbsp;\u00b0C and age of 100\u2013500 million years.<ref>[https://arxiv.org/abs/1307.2886  Direct Imaging of a Cold Jovian Exoplanet in Orbit around the Sun-like Star GJ 504]</ref>\nThis list includes the four members of the multi-planet system that orbit [[HR 8799]].\n\n==Key==\nExoplanets have been discovered using several different methods for collecting or combining direct images to isolate planets from the background light of their star. [[Aperture masking interferometry|Non-Redundant Aperture Masking Interferometry]] is a method of combining the views of multiple telescopes into a single image, while the other methods are algorithms for combining multiple direct images taken from the same telescope.\n\n* '''ADI''' = Angular Differential Imaging\n*'''KLIP''' = Karhunen\u2013Lo\u00e8ve Image Processing\n* '''LOCI''' = Locally Optimized Combination of Images\n* '''NRM''' = Non-Redundant Aperture Masking Interferometry\n* '''RSDI''' = Reference Star Differential Imaging\n*'''SDI''' = Spectral Differential Imaging\n* '''TLOCI''' = Template Locally Optimized Combination of Images\n\n==Exoplanets==\n\nAlthough listed in the table below, the identity of [[Fomalhaut b]] is disputed. It may not actually be a true exoplanet.\n\n<span style=\"margin:0px; padding-bottom:1px; font-size:90%; display:block;\"><span style=\"border:#aaa solid 1px;>&nbsp;&nbsp;\u2020&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;There is no consensus whether these companions of stars should be considered [[sub-brown dwarf]]s or planets</span>\n\nCheck https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/imaging.html to see more directly imaged planets. It contains an updated table of all of them.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" width=\"85%\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n! width=\"13%\" scope=\"col\"|[[Star]]\n! width=\"14%\" scope=\"col\"|[[Exoplanet]]\n! width=\"8%\" scope=\"col\"|[[Planetary mass|Mass]] ([[Jupiter mass|M<sub>J</sub>]])\n! width=\"8%\" scope=\"col\"|[[Radius]] ([[Jupiter radius|R<sub>J</sub>]])\n! width=\"8%\" scope=\"col\"|[[Orbital period|Period]] ([[Year|yr]])\n! width=\"8%\" scope=\"col\"|Observed separation ([[Astronomical Unit|AU]])\n! width=\"8%\" scope=\"col\"|[[Orbital eccentricity|Eccentricity]]\n! width=\"8%\" scope=\"col\"|Distance to Earth (ly)\n! width=\"8%\" scope=\"col\"|Year of discovery\n! width=\"10%\" scope=\"col\"|Imaging technique\n! width=\"4%\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Ref(s).\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=\"center\" style=\"font-weight:normal;\"| [[Beta Pictoris]]\n| [[Beta Pictoris b]] || 12.7{{\u00b1|0.3}} || 1.5{{\u00b1|0.2}} || 22.47{{\u00b1|3.77|2.26}} || 9 || 0.08{{\u00b1|0.09|-0.05}}