December ===\n[[File:JohannaAnderson1905.tif|thumb|110px|[[Johanna Anderson]]]]\n[[File:Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric de Hohenzollern-Sigmaringen.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Prince Frederick of Hohenzollern-Sigmaringen]]]]\n[[File:Mahmoud Sami Al Baroudy Pasha.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Mahmoud Samy El Baroudy]]]]\n\n* [[December 1]]\n** [[Johanna Anderson]], Swedish [[Baptist]] missionary (b. [[1856]])\n** [[Hector Giacomelli]], French artist (b. [[1822]])\n* [[December 2]]\n** [[Enrico Carfagnini]], Italian [[Roman Catholic]] friar and bishop (b. [[1823]])\n** [[Prince Frederick of Hohenzollern-Sigmaringen]] (b. [[1843]])\n* [[December 4]] &ndash; [[Cristiano Banti]], Italian painter (b. [[1824]])\n* [[December 8]] &ndash; [[John Kirkpatrick (politician)|John Kirkpatrick]], British-born Australian politician (b. [[1840]])\n* [[December 11]]\n** [[Spencer Charrington]], English brewer and politician (b. [[1818]])\n** [[Mahmoud Samy El Baroudy]], Egyptian political figure, 5th [[Prime Minister of Egypt]] (b. [[1839]])\n* [[December 13]]\n** [[Bob Murphy (baseball)|Bob Murphy]], American baseball player (b. [[1866]])\n** [[Nikolay Sklifosovsky]], Russian surgeon (b. [[1836]])\n** [[Henry Freeman (lifeboatman)|Henry Freeman]], English fisherman and lifeboatmen (b. [[1835]])\n* [[December 14]] &ndash; [[M\u00e9lanie Calvat]], French [[Roman Catholic]] nun, Marian visionary and saint (b. [[1831]])\n* [[December 16]] &ndash; [[Daniel W. Mills]], [[U.S. Representative]] from [[Illinois]] (b. [[1838]])\n* [[December 19]] &ndash; [[Lewis Tappan Barney]], American army officer (b. [[1844]])\n* [[December 20]] &ndash; [[Princess Alexandrine of Baden]] (b. [[1820]])\n* [[December 21]] &ndash; [[Edward H. Dewey]], American physician (b. [[1837]])\n* [[December 22]] &ndash; [[Horace Sumner Lyman]], American journalist (b. [[1855]])\n* [[December 24]] &ndash; [[Gustav Bauernfeind]], German painter (b. [[1848]])\n* [[December 25]] &ndash; [[Guido Bodl\u00e4nder]], German chemist (b. [[1855]])\n* [[December 27]] &ndash; [[William F. Mahoney]], [[U.S. Representative]] from [[Illinois]] (b. [[1856]])\n* [[December 29]] &ndash; [[Friedrich Moritz Brauer]], German entomologist (b. [[1832]])\n* [[December 30]] &ndash; [[Frederick Clifford]], English journalist (b. [[1828]])\n\n=== Date Unknown ===\n* [[Phoebe Jane Babcock Wait]], American physician (b. [[1838]])\n\n== Nobel Prizes ==\n[[File:Nobel medal.png|right|100px]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Physics]] &ndash; [[John William Strutt, 3rd Baron Rayleigh|The Lord Rayleigh]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Chemistry]] &ndash; Sir [[William Ramsay]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Physiology or Medicine]] &ndash; [[Ivan Pavlov|Ivan Petrovich Pavlov]]\n* [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Literature]] &ndash; [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Mistral]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Echegaray]]\n* [[Nobel Peace Prize|Peace]] &ndash; [[Institut de Droit International]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gilbert, Martin. ''A History of the Twentieth Century: Volume 1 1900-1933'' (1997); global coverage of politics, diplomacy and warfare; pp 89\u2013104.\n\n[[Category:1904| ]]\n[[Category:Leap years in the Gregorian calendar]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1904}}\n{{Year nav|1904}}\n{{C20 year in topic}}\n{{Year article header|1904}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January ===\n[[File:Baltimore fire aftermath.jpg|thumb|270px|right| [[February 7]]: Aftermath of the [[Great Baltimore Fire]].]]\n* [[January 7]] &ndash; The [[distress signal]] ''[[CQD]]'' is established, only to be replaced 2 years later by ''[[SOS]]''.\n* [[January 8]] &ndash; The [[Blackstone Library]] is dedicated, marking the beginning of the Chicago Public Library system.\n*[[January 12]] &ndash; [[Henry Ford]] sets a new automobile [[land speed record]] of {{convert|91.37|mph|abbr=on}}.\n* [[January 16]] &ndash; The first large-scale [[bodybuilding#Early years|bodybuilding]] competition in America takes place at [[Madison Square Garden (1890)|Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City]]. \n* [[January 18]] &ndash; The [[Herero Rebellion]] in [[German South-West Africa]] begins.\n* [[January 23]] &ndash; The [[\u00c5lesund Fire]] destroys most buildings in the town of [[\u00c5lesund]], Norway, leaving about 10,000 people without shelter.\n* [[January 25]] &ndash; [[Halford Mackinder]] presents a paper on \"[[The Geographical Pivot of History]]\" to the [[Royal Geographical Society]] of London in which he formulates the [[Heartland Theory]], originating the study of [[geopolitics]].\n\n=== February ===\n* [[February 7]] &ndash; The [[Great Baltimore Fire]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], destroys over 1,500 buildings in 30 hours.\n[[File:Port Arthur from Gold Hill.jpg|thumb|right|115px|Port Arthur from Gold Hill]]\n* [[February 8]]&ndash;[[February 9|9]] &ndash; [[Battle of Port Arthur]]: A surprise Japanese naval attack on [[L\u00fcshunkou District|Port Arthur]] (L\u00fcshun) in [[Manchuria]] starts the [[Russo-Japanese War]].\n* [[February 10]] &ndash; [[Roger Casement]] publishes his account of Belgian atrocities in the [[Congo Free State|Congo]].\n* [[February 17]] &ndash; [[Giacomo Puccini|Puccini]]'s opera ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'', with a background theme of [[Japan\u2013United States relations]], debuts at [[La Scala]] in [[Milan]], to no great acclaim. On [[May 28]] a revised version opens in [[Brescia]], to huge success.\n* [[February 23]] &ndash; For $10 million, the United States gains control of the [[Panama Canal]] Zone.\n* [[February 28]] &ndash; [[S.L. Benfica|Sport Lisboa e Benfica]] is founded in [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]].\n\n=== March ===\n* [[March 3]] &ndash; Kaiser [[Wilhelm II of Germany]] becomes the first person to make a political recording of a document, using [[Thomas Edison]]'s [[Phonograph cylinder|cylinder]].\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; [[Russo-Japanese War]]: [[Russian Empire|Russia]]n troops in Korea retreat toward [[Manchuria]], followed by 100,000 [[Empire of Japan|Japan]]ese troops.\n* [[March 26]] &ndash; 80,000 demonstrators gather in [[Hyde Park, London]], to protest against the importation of [[Chinese South Africans|Chinese labourers to South Africa]] by the [[Unionist Government 1895\u20131905|British government]].\n* [[March 31]] &ndash; [[British expedition to Tibet]]: The Battle of Guru &ndash; British troops under Colonel [[Francis Younghusband]] defeat ill-equipped [[Tibet]]an troops.\n\n=== April ===\n* [[April 6]] &ndash; [[Joseph F. Smith]] announces the [[Second Manifesto]] in [[General Conference (LDS Church)|General Conference]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], ending in fact the practice of plural marriage, which had continued to be practiced by many of its leaders, in violation of the [[1890 Manifesto]] officially banning the practice.\n* [[April 8]]\n** The [[Entente Cordiale]] is signed between the UK and France.\n** [[Longacre Square]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]] is renamed [[Times Square]], after ''[[The New York Times]]''.\n* [[April 8]]&ndash;[[April 10|10]] &ndash; [[Aleister Crowley]] writes ''Liber Al vel Legis'', better known as ''[[The Book of the Law]]'', a text central to [[Thelema]].\n* [[April 19]] &ndash; The [[Great Fire of Toronto (1904)|Great Toronto Fire]] destroys much of that city's downtown, but there are no fatalities.\n* [[April 27]] &ndash; The [[Australian Labor Party]] becomes the first such party to gain national government, under [[Chris Watson]].\n* [[April 30]] &ndash; The [[Louisiana Purchase Exposition]] [[World's Fair]] opens in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] (closes [[December 1]]).\n\n=== May ===\n* [[May 4]]\n** United States Army engineers begin work on the [[Panama Canal]].\n** German Association football club [[FC Schalke 04]] is established.\n* [[May 5]]\n** [[Pitcher|Pitching]] against the [[Oakland Athletics|Philadelphia Athletics]], [[Cy Young]] of the [[Boston Red Sox|Boston Americans]] throws the first [[Perfect game (baseball)|perfect game]] in the modern era of [[baseball]].\n** [[British expedition to Tibet]]: Hundreds of Tibetans attack the British camp at Changlo, and hold the advantage for a while, before being defeated by superior weapons, and losing at least 200 men.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grant|first=Neil|title=Chronicle of 20th Century Conflict|year=1993|publisher=Reed International Books Ltd. & Smithmark Publishers Inc|location=New York City|isbn=0-8317-1371-2|pages=[https://archive.org/details/chronicleof20thc00gran/page/18 18\u201319]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/chronicleof20thc00gran/page/18}}</ref>\n* [[May 9]] &ndash; [[Great Western Railway]] of England [[GWR 3440 City of Truro|3700 Class 3440 ''City of Truro'']] becomes the first railway [[locomotive]] to exceed 100&nbsp;mph (probably).\n* [[May 15]] &ndash; [[Russo-Japanese War]]: [[Russian Empire|Russian]] [[minelayer]] ''Amur'' lays a [[minefield]] about {{convert|15|mi|km}} off [[L\u00fcshunkou District|Port Arthur]], and sinks Japan's battleships [[Japanese battleship Hatsuse|''Hatsuse'']], 15,000 tons, with 496 crew and [[Japanese battleship Yashima|''Yashima'']].\n* [[May 21]] &ndash; The International Federation of Association Football, [[FIFA]], is established.\n* [[May 30]] &ndash; [[Alpha Gamma Delta]], which becomes an international women's fraternity, is founded by 11 women at [[Syracuse University]].\n\n=== June ===\n* [[June 3]] &ndash; The [[International Alliance of Women]] is founded.\n* [[June 10]] &ndash; Irish author [[James Joyce]] meets his future wife, [[Nora Barnacle]], in Dublin.\n* [[June 15]] &ndash; A fire aboard the steamboat ''[[General Slocum]]'' in New York City's East River kills 1,021.\n* [[June 16]]\n** Finnish nationalist [[Eugen Schauman]] assassinates [[Nikolay Bobrikov]], the Russian [[Governor-General of Finland]], in Helsinki.\n** [[James Joyce]] walks to [[Ringsend]] with [[Nora Barnacle]]; he later uses this date ([[Bloomsday]]) as the setting for his novel ''[[Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]]''.\n* [[June 28]]\n** Danish ocean liner {{SS|Norge}} runs aground and sinks close to [[Rockall]], killing 635, including 225 Norwegian emigrants.\n** The original icon of [[Our Lady of Kazan]] is stolen and subsequently destroyed in Russia.\n** English Association football club [[Hull City A.F.C.]] is established.\n* [[June 29]] &ndash; The [[1904 Moscow tornado]] occurs.\n\n=== July ===\n[[File:1904summerolympicsposter.jpg|thumb|100px|[[1904 Summer Olympics]]]]\n[[File:Pavlos Melas Photograph.JPG|thumb|100px|[[Pavlos Melas]]]]\n* [[July]] &ndash; [[Pavlos Melas]] enters [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]] with a small unit of men during the [[Macedonian Struggle]].\n* [[July 1]] &ndash; The [[1904 Summer Olympics|third Modern Olympic Games]] opens in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], United States as part of the [[Louisiana Purchase Exposition|World's Fair]] (the 1st [[Summer Olympic Games]] of the [[20th Century]]).\n\n=== August ===\n* [[August 3]] &ndash; [[British expedition to Tibet]]: The [[British Empire|British]] expedition under Colonel [[Francis Younghusband]] takes [[Lhasa (prefecture-level city)|Lhasa]], [[Tibet]].\n* [[August 11]] &ndash; [[Battle of Waterberg]]: [[Lothar von Trotha]] defeats the [[Herero people]] in [[German South-West Africa]], and drives them into the [[Omaheke]] desert, starting the [[Herero and Namaqua Genocide]].\n* [[August 14]] &ndash; [[Ismael Montes]] becomes [[President of Bolivia]].\n* [[August 17]] &ndash; [[Russo-Japanese War]]: A Japanese infantry charge fails to take [[L\u00fcshunkou|Port Arthur]].\n* [[August 18]] &ndash; [[Chris Watson]] resigns as [[Prime Minister of Australia]], and is succeeded by [[George Reid (Australian politician)|George Reid]].\n* [[August 24]] &ndash; Faroese Association football club [[Klaksv\u00edkar \u00cdtr\u00f3ttarfelag]] is established.\n\n=== September ===\n* September &ndash; [[Stuyvesant High School]] opens in New York City as Manhattan's first manual trade school for boys.\n* [[September 1]] &ndash; [[Griffin Park]] football stadium opens to the public in London.\n* [[September 2]] &ndash; [[John Voss (sailor)|John Voss]] sails the rigged [[dugout canoe]] ''[[Tilikum (boat)|Tilikum]]'' into the [[River Thames]] in England after a 3-year voyage from [[Victoria, British Columbia]], westabout.\n* [[September 7]] &ndash; [[British expedition to Tibet]]: The [[Dalai Lama]] signs the Anglo-Tibetan Treaty with Colonel [[Francis Younghusband]].\n* [[September 17]] &ndash; An early study on the relationship between [[alcohol and cardiovascular disease]] is published in the United States.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cabot|first=Richard C.|authorlink=Richard Clarke Cabot|title=The relation of alcohol to arterioscleroisis|journal=[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]|year=1904|volume=43|issue=12|pages=774\u2013775|doi=10.1001/jama.1904.92500120002a|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1447273/files/article.pdf|accessdate=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n* [[September 25]] &ndash; [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] President [[Joseph F. Smith]] issues a ''[[1890 Manifesto|Second Manifesto]]'' against polygamy.\n* [[September 26]] &ndash; New Zealand [[dolphin]] [[Pelorus Jack]] is individually protected by [[Order in Council]] under the Sea Fisheries Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/1966/P/PelorusJack/PelorusJack/en|accessdate=2006-12-29|last=Alpers|first=A. F. G.|title= Pelorus Jack|work=An Encyclopaedia of New Zealand|year=1966}}</ref>\n\n=== October ===\n* October &ndash; The Daytona Educational and Industrial Training School for Negro Girls, predecessor of [[Bethune\u2013Cookman University]], is opened in Florida by [[Mary McLeod Bethune]].\n* [[October 1]] &ndash; [[Phi Delta Epsilon]], the international medical fraternity, is founded by Aaron Brown and 8 of his friends, at [[Cornell University Medical College]].\n* [[October 4]] &ndash; [[Sweden|Swedish]] Association football club [[IFK G\u00f6teborg]] is founded, becoming the 39th [[Idrottsf\u00f6reningen Kamraterna|IFK-association]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifkgoteborg.se/Om-IFK-Goteborg/Presentation/Historik/bla/|title=IFK - 1904-1908|website=www.ifkgoteborg.se|language=Swedish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401123900/http://www.ifkgoteborg.se/Om-IFK-Goteborg/Presentation/Historik/bla/|archive-date=April 1, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=2017-11-03|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[October 5]] &ndash; [[Alpha Kappa Psi]], a co-ed professional [[business]] fraternity, is founded on the campus of [[New York University]].\n* [[October 9]] &ndash; German journalist [[Anna R\u00fcling]], in a speech to the [[Scientific-Humanitarian Committee]] in Berlin, makes the [[List of lesbian, gay, bisexual, or transgender firsts by year|first known]] public statement of the socio-legal problems faced by [[lesbian]]s.\n* [[October 11]] &ndash; [[Loftus Road]] football stadium opens in London.\n* [[October 13]] &ndash; [[Pavlos Melas]] is encircled at [[Melas, Kastoria|Statista]] and killed during the [[Macedonian Struggle]].\n* [[October 15]] &ndash; [[Theta Tau]], a [[Professional fraternity|professional]] engineering fraternity, is founded at the [[University of Minnesota]] in [[Minneapolis]].\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; [[Polytechnic University of the Philippines]] is founded as Manila Business School, through the superintendence of American C.A. O'Reilley.\n* [[October 21]] &ndash; [[Russo-Japanese War]]: [[Dogger Bank incident]] &ndash; The Russian [[Baltic Fleet]] fires on British trawlers it mistakes for Japanese torpedo boats, in the [[North Sea]].\n* [[October 27]] &ndash; The first underground line of the [[New York City Subway]] opens.\n* [[October 28]] &ndash; [[Panama]] and [[Uruguay]] establish [[Panama\u2013Uruguay relations|diplomatic links]].\n\n=== November ===\n[[Image:President Theodore Roosevelt, 1904.jpg|thumb|right|115px|[[November 8]]: Republican [[Theodore Roosevelt]] is elected President of the United States by defeating Democrat [[Alton B. Parker]].]]\n[[File:Leclerc p1040868.jpg|thumb|180px|right| [[November 24]]: [[caterpillar track]]]]\n* [[November 8]] &ndash; [[U.S. presidential election, 1904]]: Republican incumbent [[Theodore Roosevelt]] defeats Democrat [[Alton B. Parker]].\n* [[November 16]] \n** The settlement at [[Grytviken]], on the British South Atlantic island territory of [[South Georgia Island|South Georgia]], is established by Norwegian sea captain [[Carl Anton Larsen]], as a [[whaling]] station for his ''[[Compa\u00f1\u00eda Argentina de Pesca]]''.<ref>{{cite book|first=R. K.|last=Headland|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lZ04AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Island of South Georgia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1984|isbn=0-521-25274-1}}</ref>\n** English engineer [[John Ambrose Fleming]] receives a patent for the thermionic valve (vacuum tube).\n* [[November 24]] &ndash; The first successful [[caterpillar track]] is made (it later revolutionizes construction vehicles and land warfare).\n\n=== December ===\n* [[December 2]] &ndash; The [[St. Petersburg Soviet]] urges a [[run on the bank]]s; the attempt fails, and the executive committee is arrested.\n* [[December 3]] &ndash; [[Charles Dillon Perrine]] discovers [[Jupiter]]'s largest [[irregular satellite]], [[Himalia (moon)|Himalia]], at California's [[Lick Observatory]].\n* [[December 4]] &ndash; The K.U. or [[Konservativ Ungdom]] (Young Conservatives) is founded by Carl F. Herman von Rosen in Denmark.\n* [[December 6]] &ndash; [[Theodore Roosevelt]] announces his [[Roosevelt Corollary|\"Corollary\"]] to the [[Monroe Doctrine]], stating that the United States will intervene in the Western Hemisphere, should Latin American governments prove incapable or unstable.\n* [[December 10]] &ndash; The [[Pi Kappa Phi]] fraternity is founded at the [[College of Charleston]] in Charleston, South Carolina.\n* [[December 27]] &ndash; The stage play ''[[Peter Pan]], or The Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up'' premieres in London.\n* [[December 30]] &ndash; The [[East Boston Tunnel]] opens.\n* [[December 31]] &ndash; In New York City, the first [[New Year's Eve]] celebration is held in [[Times Square]].\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* [[St. Bernard's School]] is founded in New York City on Manhattan.\n\n== Births ==\n\n=== January ===\n[[File:The Wizard of Oz Ray Bolger 1939.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Ray Bolger]]]]\n[[File:Grant, Cary (Suspicion) 01 Crisco edit.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Cary Grant]]]]\n* [[January 1]] &ndash; [[Fazal Ilahi Chaudhry]], Pakistani politician (d. [[1982]])\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; [[Jeane Dixon]], American astrologer (d. [[1997]])\n* [[January 6]] &ndash; [[Ramiro Prial\u00e9]], Peruvian politician (d. [[1988]])\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Ray Bolger]], American actor, singer and dancer, best known for his role in ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (d. [[1987]])\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; [[Richard Addinsell]], British composer (d. [[1977]])\n* [[January 14]]\n**[[Hector Grey]], Scottish street trader and company director (d. [[1985]])\n**[[Cecil Beaton]], English photographer (d. [[1980]])\n**[[Ernst Wellmann]], highly decorated German Army officer (d. [[1970]])\n* [[January 18]] &ndash; [[Cary Grant]], English actor (d. [[1986]])\n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[Leo Soileau]], American [[Cajuns|Cajun]] musician (d. [[1980]])\n* [[January 21]] &ndash; [[Edris Rice-Wray Carson]], American medical researcher (d. [[1990]])\n* [[January 22]]\n** [[George Balanchine]], Russian-born choreographer (d. [[1983]])\n** [[Arkady Gaidar]], Russian children's writer (d. [[1941]])\n* [[January 26]]\n** [[Ancel Keys]], American scientist (d. [[2004]])\n** [[Donald Macintyre (Royal Navy officer)|Donald Macintyre]], British naval officer and naval historian (d. [[1981]])\n** [[Se\u00e1n MacBride]], Irish statesman, recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1988]])\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[J. J. Gibson]], American psychologist (d. [[1979]])\n* [[January 28]] &ndash; [[Canuplin]], Filipino magician, bodabil entertainer (d. [[1979]])\n* [[January 29]] &ndash; [[Arnold Gehlen]], German philosopher (d. [[1976]])\n\n=== February ===\n[[File:Keith Holyoake (1960).jpg|thumb|100px|[[Keith Holyoake]]]]\n[[File:Jimmy Dorsey Billboard 2.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Jimmy Dorsey]]]]\n* [[February 1]]\n** [[\u00c1ngel Borlenghi]], Argentine labor leader, politician (d. [[1962]])\n** [[S. J. Perelman]], American humorist, author (d. [[1979]])\n* [[February 2]] &ndash; [[Valery Chkalov]], Soviet test pilot (d. [[1938]])\n* [[February 3]]\n** [[Luigi Dallapiccola]], Italian composer (d. [[1975]])\n** [[Pretty Boy Floyd]], American gangster (d. [[1934]])\n* [[February 4]] &ndash; [[MacKinlay Kantor]], American writer, historian (d. [[1977]])\n* [[February 10]] &ndash; [[John Farrow]], Australian film director (d. [[1963]])\n* [[February 11]] \n** [[Jos\u00e9 do Patroc\u00ednio Oliveira]], Brazilian musician and voice actor (d. [[1987]])\n** Sir [[Keith Holyoake]], 26th [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] (d. [[1983]])\n** [[Lucile Randon]], French supercentenarian\n* [[February 16]]\n** [[James Baskett]], African-American actor (Uncle Remus in Disney's [[Song of the South]]) (d. [[1948]])\n** [[George F. Kennan]], American diplomat (d. [[2005]])\n** [[Philip Rabinowitz (runner)|Philip Rabinowitz]], South African record-breaking sprinter (d. [[2008]])\n* [[February 21]] &ndash; [[Alexei Kosygin]], Premier of the Soviet Union (d. [[1980]])\n* [[February 22]] &ndash; [[Ernst Jakob Henne]], German motorcycle racer, racecar driver (d. [[2005]])\n* [[February 23]] \n** [[Gaston Marie Jacquier]], French Roman Catholic bishop in Algeria (d. [[1976]])\n** [[William L. Shirer]], American journalist, author (d. [[1993]])\n* [[February 29]] &ndash; [[Jimmy Dorsey]], American bandleader (d. [[1957]])\n\n=== March ===\n[[File:Ted Geisel NYWTS 2 crop.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Dr. Seuss]]]]\n[[File:Joan Crawford - 1936 - Hurrell.JPG|thumb|100px|[[Joan Crawford]]]]\n* [[March 1]]\n** [[Glenn Miller]], American bandleader (d. [[1944]])\n** [[Paul Hartman]], American actor, dancer (d. [[1973]])\n* [[March 2]] &ndash; [[Dr. Seuss]], American children's author (''The Cat in the Hat'') (d. [[1991]])\n* [[March 4]]\n** [[Luis Carrero Blanco]], Prime Minister of Spain (d. [[1973]])\n** [[George Gamow]], Ukrainian-born physicist (d. [[1968]])\n** [[Joseph Schmidt]], Austrian-Hungarian tenor, actor (d. [[1942]])\n** [[Chief Tahachee]], American-born stage, film actor (d. [[1978]])\n* [[March 5]] &ndash; [[Mow Pang Tzu]], [[Republic of China]] air force general (d. [[1987]])\n* [[March 6]] &ndash; [[Hugh Williams]], English actor, dramatist (d. [[1969]])\n* [[March 7]] &ndash; [[Reinhard Heydrich]], German Nazi official (d. [[1942]])\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Doris Eaton Travis]], American actress (d. [[2010]])\n* [[March 15]] &ndash; [[J. Pat O'Malley]], English actor (d. [[1985]])\n* [[March 20]]\n** [[Frank Mills (politician)]], American politician in Ohio legislature (d. [[1969]])\n** [[B. F. Skinner]], American behavioral psychologist (d. [[1990]])\n* [[March 22]] &ndash; [[Itche Goldberg]], Yiddish author (d. [[2006]])\n* [[March 23]] &ndash; [[Joan Crawford]], American actress (d. [[1977]]) (other sources report her year of birth as 1903, 1905, 1906, and 1908) \n* [[March 26]]\n** [[Emilio Fern\u00e1ndez]], Mexican film director, actor and screenwriter (d. [[1986]])\n** [[Gustave Bi\u00e9ler]], Swiss-born hero of World War II (executed) (d. [[1944]])\n** [[Joseph Campbell]], American author on mythology (d. [[1987]])\n* [[March 30]] \n** [[Alexandrina Maria da Costa]], Portuguese [[Roman Catholic]] mystic, victim soul and blessed (d. [[1955]])\n** [[Shin Matsushita]], Japanese supercentenarian (d. [[2019]])\n\n=== April ===\n[[File:SharkeyBandstand1950Kubrick.JPG|thumb|100px|[[Sharkey Bonano]]]]\n[[File:Sir John Gielgud actor.jpg|thumb|100px|[[John Gielgud]]]]\n[[File:JROppenheimer-LosAlamos.jpg|thumb|100px|[[J. Robert Oppenheimer]]]]\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[Nikolai Berzarin]], Russian Red Army General (d. [[1945]])\n* [[April 3]] &ndash; [[Sally Rand]], American dancer, actress (d. [[1979]])\n* [[April 4]] &ndash; [[Soeman Hs]], Indonesian author, educator (d. [[1999]])\n* [[April 6]]\n** [[William Challee]], American actor (d. [[1989]]) \n** [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]], former Chancellor of West Germany (d. [[1988]])\n* [[April 8]] &ndash; [[John Hicks]], English economist, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1989]])\n* [[April 9]] &ndash; [[Sharkey Bonano]], American jazz musician (d. [[1972]])\n* [[April 10]] &ndash; [[Nino Pavese]], Italian actor and voice actor (d. [[1979]])\n* [[April 13]] &ndash; [[Elwood Richard Quesada]], American air force general (d. [[1993]])\n* [[April 14]] &ndash; [[John Gielgud]], English actor (d. [[2000]])\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; [[Arshile Gorky]], Armenian-born painter (d. [[1948]])\n* [[April 16]] &ndash; [[Fifi D'Orsay]], Canadian actress (d. [[1983]])\n* [[April 22]] &ndash; [[J. Robert Oppenheimer]], American physicist (d. [[1967]])\n* [[April 24]] &ndash; [[Willem de Kooning]], Dutch artist (d. [[1997]])\n* [[April 26]]\n** [[Jimmy McGrory]], Scottish footballer (d. [[1982]])\n** [[Xenophon Zolotas]], Prime Minister of Greece (d. [[2004]])\n* [[April 27]]\n** [[Cecil Day-Lewis]], English poet (d. [[1972]])\n** [[Syd Nathan]], American record producer, [[music industry]] executive and founder of [[King Records (United States)|King Records]] (d. [[1968]])\n* [[April 29]] &ndash; [[Pedro Vargas]], Mexican singer, actor (d. [[1989]])\n\n=== May ===\n[[File:Salvador Dal\u00ed 1939.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]]]\n[[File:Fats Waller edit.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Fats Waller]]]]\n[[File:RobertMontgomeryApr1939.jpg|thumb|100px|[[Robert Montgomery (actor)|Robert Montgomery]]]]\n* [[May 4]]\n** [[Umm Kulthum]], Egyptian singer and actress (d. [[1975]])\n** [[Joaqu\u00edn Garc\u00eda Morato]], Spanish fighte